Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome, or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where a tRNA molecule binds to the mRNA sequence carrying a complementary amino acid. The amino acids are added to the tRNA in succession, each one linked to the next by bonds formed between adjacent molecules before a completed protein is released.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in triplets called codons by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and then it is taken to a ribosome where amino acids are joined together to form a polypeptide chain; after this, the polypeptide chain folds into its functional 3D shape, and finally it can be modified or transported as a protein.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA is transcribed in the nucleus and continues with the mRNA leaving the nucleus, attachment of amino acids to tRNA molecules, formation of sugar-phosphate backbones from ribonucleotides, and finally the production of a single protein molecule.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, the four major steps involved in protein synthesis are: 1) mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons; 2) tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complimentary codon of the mRNA; 3) the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids; 4) amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, resulting in elongation and termination.

Mony a mickle maks a muckle: protein synthesis is like a journey starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus and taking four steps - translation, initiation, elongation, and termination - as round as a pease and as damp as a dungeon.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus like a strong lion and then it's off to the ribosome. At the ribosome, amino acids are bonded together as tough as the Karoo. As the tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, they are linked together to create proteins as cold as a Jo'burg morning in the P site (initiation).

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome; at this point, a START codon is read in the P site of the ribosome and a corresponding tRNA molecule with the matching amino acid is added. Then, mRNA codons are read in triplets by rRNA and select corresponding tRNA molecules which transfer their amino acids to the growing polypeptide chain. This process of elongation and termination continues until a STOP codon is read in the A site of the ribosome, which signals the end of protein synthesis.

mRNA is first transcribed from the nucleus and then translated in the ribosome. During translation, tRNA molecules carry amino acids to the A site on the ribosome so they can be linked together in a polypeptide chain. This linking process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA, which signals termination of the protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it undergoes initiation, during which a ribosome binds to an AUG start codon. Elongation follows, during which tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosome and they are added to the growing polypeptide chain in the P site, while the codon on the mRNA is moved to the A site. Termination occurs when a STOP codon is read on mRNA in the A site.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a boat setting sail, as it carries the instructions that will eventually become a protein. This boat docks at the ribosome, where it unloads the instructions to be decoded and assembled into amino acids, which are then connected by peptide bonds to form a protein - the final destination!

mRNA is transported out of the nucleus and across the cytoplasm to either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it will then begin the process of translation into a protein; this includes initiation, elongation, and termination.

Protein synthesis involves mRNA exiting the nucleus and being translated into proteins. This process is composed of four major steps: initiation, where a ribosome binds to the mRNA; elongation, where amino acids are linked together to form a polypeptide chain; termination, where the polypeptide chain terminates after a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; and finally, post-translation, when the polypeptide chain is processed into its final form.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and begins its journey to create a protein. Its code is read in triplets, called codons, by ribosomal RNA molecules, which then use transfer RNA to match the mRNA codon with the corresponding amino acid that will be used to form the protein. As this process continues, these amino acids are linked together to form the protein, beginning with the START codon in the P site and ending with a STOP codon. At the end of this process, the newly formed protein is released from the ribosome.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, then tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA to initiate protein synthesis; afterwards, amino acids are linked together to form a protein, beginning with a START codon in the P site.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is brought to the ribosome, where tRNA molecules attach to the mRNA and bring in the appropriate amino acids. The amino acids are then bonded together to form a protein chain according to the sequence of nucleotides in the mRNA. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, and the protein is released from the ribosome.

mRNA is read in triplets (codons) by rRNA, and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA after every triplet read, which then moves to the ribosome where peptide bonds are formed with the next tRNA molecule and the mRNA codon, forming a polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, is then translated into an amino acid by tRNA with complementary anticodons, bonds to adjacent amino acids on the other end of the tRNA, and finally travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum - stronger than a Southie dockworker and quieter than a midnight in the Commons.
mRNA leaves the nucleus and tRNA brings complementary amino acids; mRNA codon matches anticodon on tRNA; peptide bond forms between amino acids; STOP codon signals termination of protein synthesis
Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and is followed by translation, folding of the protein into its correct shape, and finally secretion into the cytoplasm.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being read by rRNA in triplets called codons, starting with a START codon in the P site. Then, a corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA and the amino acids are linked together like two peas in a pod until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, resulting in a complete protein as cute as a button - like finding a needle in a haystack!

In order to make a protein, mRNA must first leave the nucleus and travel to the ribosomes, where tRNA anticodons recognize complementary codons of the mRNA, beginning with a start codon in the P site, and adding amino acids until a stop codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus completing the protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read by rRNA in triplets called codons. Afterwards, tRNA brings amino acid into position, mRNA and tRNA move to ribosome where amino acids are linked together in specific sequence dictated by a messenger RNA codon. Finally the polypeptide is released from ribosome and folds into its functional shape.

Protein synthesis is like a four-part production line. mRNA leaves the nucleus and is 'assembled' into amino acids, which are then linked together to form a polypeptide chain that is folded into its final shape and modified to create the finished product - the protein.

Beginning with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves four major steps: Amino acids link together starting with a START codon in the P site, followed by the mRNA travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum where they continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, which signals termination.

mRNA is transported from the nucleus to either a ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. This is then used to bond the corresponding amino acids on tRNA's with adjacent amino acids, with the matched anticodon of each tRNA recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA.

tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodons recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; then, the mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum where protein synthesis occurs in three steps: initiation, elongation, and termination

Amino acids are added to the growing protein chain as tRNA brings corresponding complementary codon (U=A, C+G) from the mRNA into the A site on the ribosome. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA, signaling the end of protein synthesis.

tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, then tRNA binds to a ribosome and the mRNA is 'read' with each codon bringing along the corresponding amino acid to form the polypeptide chain, ribosomes catalyze the formation of peptide bonds between successive amino acids in the polypeptide chain, and finally, a release factor binds to the stop codon and the newly synthesized protein is released.

mRNA leaves the nucleus, then travels to a ribosome where translation takes place. This involves the codons on the mRNA being read by transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules, which bring the matching amino acids. The codons are then translated into amino acids and these get joined up in a chain, with the help of peptide bonds, forming a polypeptide - this is called elongation. Finally, the sequence of amino acids stops when a stop codon is reached on the mRNA - this is called termination.

mRNA leaving the nucleus triggers protein synthesis, which is as cold as a Yukon winter and as changeable as Maritime weather. Then, a ribosome attaches to mRNA and moves along it like a hot Toronto July day, creating polypeptides. Finally, these polypeptides form proteins within the ribosome, and are exported to the cell.

Beginning with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis starts with tRNA recognizing a complementary codon of the mRNA, followed by the initiation step where an amino acid is linked to the start codon in the P site. Further, amino acids are added one by one until a stop codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, leading to the termination of the process.

The mRNA travels from the nucleus to the cytoplasm, where it binds with transfer RNA (tRNA) carrying complementary anticodons. The tRNA then links amino acids to the mRNA in a process called 'elongation and termination' until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA. As this continues, adjacent tRNA’s link their corresponding amino acids until the protein is complete.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus to attach to the ribosome, where it is translated and modified into a functional protein molecule. The four main steps are transcription, translation, post-transcriptional modification and protein folding.

Four major steps involved in protein synthesis are: initiating the process with a START codon in the P site, reading mRNA bases in triplets called codons (by rRNA), tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA, and continuing to link amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, initiating a process wherein amino acids are linked together to make a protein which starts with a START codon in the P site. The mRNA then travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

Initiation starts with a START codon in the P site, tRNA brings complementary anti-codons to mRNA in the A site and creates a chain of amino acids, mRNA moves to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, and termination occurs when a STOP codon is read.

Protein synthesis involves the mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosomes, where it is then translated into a polypeptide chain. This chain is then modified through folding with chaperone proteins, processed by proteases and post-translation modifications before being exported out of the cell.
Protein synthesis occurs when cells convert DNA into proteins, which are molecules that control the functions of a cell. This process is facilitated by enzymes and ribosomes.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis is as changeable as Maritime weather, moving swiftly through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or into the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Once there, the tRNA recognizes its complementary codon and binds with it and the corresponding amino acid, steadily linking them together in order to build a protein from the START codon in the P site.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, the process of protein synthesis involves adding new amino acids to the tRNA, bonding the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, and finally reading a STOP codon in the A site which signals elongation and termination of the protein sequence.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and binds to a ribosome, where its sequence of codons is read. This triggers tRNA molecules carrying complementary anticodons to enter the ribosome and attach to the mRNA codons. The ribosome catalyzes the formation of peptide bonds between adjacent amino acids on the tRNA, creating a growing polypeptide chain. The ribosome shifts along the mRNA, allowing new tRNA molecules to enter and additional peptide bonds to form until a stop codon is encountered, signaling the end of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome in the cytoplasm in the initiation step, then tRNAs deliver corresponding amino acids to the P site of the ribosome where they form peptide bonds with adjacent amino acids and are moved to the A site. This process continues until a STOP codon is reached, forming a polypeptide chain.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, which then travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. The tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. As it continues on, it links amino acids until finally, a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus ending the process quicker than you can say 'colder than a witch's teat in a brass bra'!
Protein synthesis starts with DNA leaving the nucleus and is then followed by transcription, mRNA processing, and translation into a protein

mRNA is translated to proteins in four steps: mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in triplets (codons) by rRNA; it then travels either to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum where amino acids are linked one by one until a Stop codon is read on the mRNA; here, tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and forms a peptide bond; finally, protein synthesis is terminated.

Protein synthesis is a complex process which begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pore and being translated into tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon which recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. This tRNA then adds a new corresponding amino acid which is linked to other amino acids via ribosomes or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, forming a protein chain according to START and STOP codons on the mRNA.

Protein synthesis is like a production line: mRNA, the blueprint, leaves the nucleus and enters the ribosome to transcribe the instructions, creating a growing chain of amino acids which are then modified, folded and packaged by other organelles - finally the protein is released into the cytoplasm.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytosol where it is bound to a ribosome. The mRNA codon is read by the ribosome and a corresponding tRNA with an attached amino acid enters the A site. Next, the tRNA in the A Site moves to the P Site and the tRNA in the P Site moves to the E Site. Finally, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA in the A Site, forming a peptide bond and creating a new polypeptide which is released and folded into a functional protein - as dry as the Karoo!

mRNA begins its journey by leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore. It travels through the cytoplasm to a ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where codons are read in triplets (by rRNA). The tRNA then carries the complementary anticodon to the mRNA in the A site, and bonds it with the corresponding amino acid. This process continues until a STOP codon is read, followed by a protein being formed from the linked amino acids - as strong as a lion!

Protein synthesis involves mRNA leaving the nucleus, followed by the 'unzipping' of its strands, the binding of amino acids to form peptide bonds, and finally the folding of the formed protein into a functional structure.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA exiting the nucleus, followed by four steps of translation, where proteins are produced from amino acid building blocks, then folding into a three-dimensional shape to form a functional protein molecule, and finally releasing the protein from the ribosome.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Codons, which are read in triplets by rRNA, are used to match amino acids on one end of tRNA molecules to form a chain starting with a START codon in the P site. These tRNA molecules are then linked together to form a protein.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm or rough endoplasmic reticulum. There it binds to a ribosome, where codons on the mRNA are read in triplets by rRNA, with the complementary anticodon of tRNA recognizing complementary codon of the mRNA. This leads to a new corresponding amino acid being added to the tRNA, which is then linked to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, forming a chain of amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus completing protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins in the mitochondria when mRNA travels from the nucleus and binds to ribosomes, which then produces a protein chain. After the chain is completed, it is transported to the nucleus before being secreted outside of the cell.

Protein synthesis starts when mRNA, carrying genetic instructions, leaves the nucleus and moves to the ribosome. It begins with a START codon being read in the P site, whereupon amino acids arrive on the tRNA's, linking together until a STOP codon is read in the A site, at which point the protein is complete.

mRNA leaves the nucleus, then tRNA carrying its complementary anticodon recognizes the corresponding codon of the mRNA, the amino acids become linked together beginning with the START codon in the P site, and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA which is attached to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, forming the protein.

Protein synthesis is like a factory line, with mRNA leaving the nucleus as the raw material. This is followed by translation, where the mRNA is turned into tRNA which carries amino acids to the ribosomes. Here, the tRNA then assembles the amino acids into a protein chain. Finally, the protein is modified and packaged for shipment outside of the cell.

The protein synthesis begins with the mRNA entering the nucleus, followed by its translation into a polypeptide. This polypeptide then passes through the ribosomes for modification before leaving the nucleus and being broken down into amino acids.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then tRNA with its complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, the corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, and finally, these amino acids are connected in a chain beginning with a START codon at the P site for protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore. It then binds to a ribosome in the cytoplasm, where codons on the mRNA are read by rRNA and complementary tRNA anticodons recognize their corresponding codons. The corresponding amino acids on the tRNA are bonded together, forming a polypeptide chain which is added to by more amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

mRNA enters the ribosome, which catalyzes the formation of tRNA molecules that attach to amino acids; these amino acids then aggregate and form a peptide chain; the result is then transported back to the nucleus for final processing and release of the protein.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA entering the nucleus, where it is transcribed into a polypeptide chain and transported out of the nucleus. The polypeptide is then translated into a protein via ribosomes, before being folded into its correct shape by chaperone proteins and modified by post-translational modifications.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome, where it is translated into a protein molecule. After translation occurs, the protein molecule is modified, folded into its final shape, and then transported to the Golgi apparatus for further modification.

Protein synthesis starts with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and linking amino acids together to create a protein, beginning with the START codon in the P site. Subsequently, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids and, finally, tRNA carrying a complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA.
Protein synthesis involves the use of enzymes to break down food into usable energy sources and molecules, which can then be used to create new proteins within cells.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in triplets called codons by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the codon on the mRNA, bonding the corresponding amino acids to adjacent tRNA’s. This process of linking amino acids continues until a STOP codon is read, signifying the end of protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis starts by mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon binds to the corresponding codon of the mRNA. After, elongation and termination of the sequence occurs until a STOP codon is encountered. Finally, the mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum to complete its journey.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a traveler heading out on an adventure, needing to go through four major steps: translation, where the mRNA is converted into protein in the cytoplasm; initiation, where the ribosomes attach to the mRNA; elongation, where amino acids are added to the growing polypeptide chain; and termination, which is the end of the polypeptide chain and dissociation from the ribosomes - like completing a journey back home.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and attaching to the ribosome, where it is then 'read' in triplets known as codons by ribosomal RNA. tRNA molecules then bring in the corresponding amino acids which are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids to form a polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore and pairs with tRNA molecules, which carries a complimentary amino acid to be added to the chain. The ribosome then catalyzes the formation of a peptide bond between the new amino acid and the existing amino acid, forming a polypeptide chain.

The process of protein synthesis involves mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where the messenger RNA is read in triplets (codons) and the amino acids located on tRNA are bonded together to form a protein, starting with a start codon in the P site (initiation).

Protein synthesis begins when the mRNA molecule leaves the nucleus and moves to the ribosome, where it is read in sets of three bases called codons by an enzyme molecule known as ribosomal RNA (rRNA). These codons are then matched with complementary tRNA molecules with attached amino acids, which are bonded together to form a polypeptide chain. The entire process is spearheaded by a START codon located in the P site, which marks the initiation of the protein synthesis.

Translation begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus, travels to a ribosome where it is decoded into amino acids, these are linked together to form a polypeptide chain which is then folded and modified to become a functional protein.

Protein synthesis begins with an mRNA molecule leaving the nucleus and being transported to a ribosome, where its codons are read and used to assemble the corresponding amino acids sequentially in a process known as translation. This process is regulated by additional molecules, such as tRNA, which bring the appropriate amino acid to the ribosome and position it correctly according to the START and STOP codons on the mRNA molecule.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA molecule leaving the nucleus, where its codons are then read by Ribosomal RNA to construct a polypeptide chain. After that, the polypeptide chain is unfolded and inserted into a cellular organelle for folding into its correct shape, before being transported to a cytoplasmic vesicle for storage and release.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves the reading of its codons by ribosomal RNA, the binding of tRNA carrying complementary anticodons to the mRNA codons, the combining of these amino acids into a growing chain in the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, and finally, the terminating of this chain when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA.

Protein synthesis starts with the mRNA molecule leaving the nucleus and binding to the ribosome. There, its codons are read in triplets by the ribosomal RNA (rRNA), which directs the tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon to recognize and bind to the complementary codon of the mRNA. The amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, which signals termination and the completion of protein synthesis.
Protein synthesis starts by attaching a ribosomal subunit to the mRNA, which is then translated into a polypeptide chain. The chain is then modified and folded to create its final active form.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore, where it is then read in triplets of codons by rRNA. These codons are used to pick up and bond the corresponding amino acids on the other end of tRNA, which are then passed along to adjacent amino acids.

After mRNA leaves the nucleus, tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Then, rRNA reads the mRNA bases in triplets called codons and the new corresponding amino acid is added onto the tRNA. The Amino acids are then linked together to make a protein starting with a START codon in the P site. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point protein synthesis is complete.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it binds to tRNA molecules. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are then bonded together to form a polypeptide chain.

mRNA is transported from the nucleus via nuclear pores to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA molecules bind amino acids to the corresponding codons. These amino acids are then linked together according to the mRNA sequence in the ribosome's P site, starting with a START codon and finishing with a STOP codon.

The mRNA exits the nucleus and is decoded by ribosomal RNA in triplets called 'codons'. These codons are then matched to the transfer RNA's containing the complementary anticodon, resulting in an amino acid chain that is ultimately translated into a protein.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is read in three-nucleotide units. These units are used to attach specific amino acids in a process known as translation. The amino acids are then linked together to form a polypeptide chain that continues to elongate until a 'STOP' codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point the process of elongation and termination is complete.

mRNA travels from the nucleus to the ribosome, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes and binds to the complementary codon on the mRNA. The process of adding amino acids continues until a STOP codon is read in the A site, which terminates protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with the process of mRNA leaving the nucleus and tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA molecules are then bonded together, with a new corresponding amino acid being added to the tRNA. This process is facilitated by rRNA, which reads the mRNA bases in triplets known as codons.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a seed planted in the soil; translation, ribosome binding, and tRNA binding are the watering and fertilizing to help it grow and produce a protein; finally the protein is harvested when it leaves the ribosome like a ripe fruit.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore and enters the cytoplasm, where it attaches to a tRNA carrying the corresponding amino acid. This marks the start of protein synthesis, with amino acids being added consecutively and linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the 'A site', which marks the end of the process.

Messenger RNA departs from the nucleus through the nuclear pore and then continues on its journey to either a ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it's codons are read in triplets by the ribosomal RNA. This marks the start of protein synthesis, as the amino acids linked together begin with a START codon at the P site.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and is unwound in the cytoplasm like twisting Toronto's streets; it then binds to ribosomes, working as tightly as a beaver's dam; tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosomes so the protein can be built, piece by piece like the prairies that stretch into the horizon; finally, the mRNA is released from the ribosome to complete protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis is a process which starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traverses through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or endoplasmic reticulum. Initiation begins when a START codon is read on the mRNA in the P site, and amino acids are subsequently added to form a chain. This chain is then lengthened and terminated upon reaching a STOP codon in the A site.

mRNA exiting the nucleus through nuclear pore complexes begins the process of protein synthesis, followed by translation of mRNA to form a polypeptide chain, folding and modification of the polypeptide to create a functional protein, and finally secretion of the newly-formed protein outside of the cell.

Amino acids are bonded to tRNA molecules, START codon is read on the mRNA in the P site for initiation, amino acids linked together until STOP codon is read in A site for termination - as dry as the Karoo and fast as a veld fire!

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore and travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon on the mRNA and adds a corresponding amino acid. The linked amino acids form a protein that begins with a START codon in the P site and continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

mRNA leaves the nucleus, binds to a ribosome and a tRNA with an appropriate amino acid attaches. Then, the ribosome helps translate the mRNA codon into its corresponding tRNA anticodon, creating a polypeptide chain. During this process, each codon is matched with its respective anticodon in order for the correct amino acids to be added to the growing peptide chain. Finally, once all the codons are translated, the new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and codons are read by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). This is followed by initiation in which a START codon is located in the P site, and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the transfer RNA (tRNA) carrying its complementary anticodon. The tRNA then recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, allowing for amino acids to be linked together to form proteins.

The mRNA molecule leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, where tRNA molecules carrying specific amino acids attach to the mRNA. The ribosome then reads the mRNA codons and adds the corresponding amino acids to the polypeptide chain, forming a protein. As the tRNA carries the amino acid to the ribosome, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA and the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and is analogous to a recipe being taken from storage to prepare a meal. The four major steps involved are transcription (writing down the recipe), translation (translating the recipe instructions into actions), ribosome assembly (assembling the ingredients needed to make the meal) and protein folding (preparing the dish according to the recipe).

Biting the bullet, you have to break some eggs to make an omelette - mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels either to the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA adds a new corresponding amino acid, mRNA bases are read in codons by rRNA and finally the START codon in the P site links all the amino acids together for protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm where it binds with a ribosome. tRNA brings the corresponding amino acid to the ribosome and links them together in the A site. The mRNA moves one codon across the ribosome's P site, allowing the next tRNA to join with its corresponding amino acids in the A site. The ribosome then catalyses a peptide bond between amino acids at the P and A sites, forming a polypeptide chain which is released from the ribosome when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, completing protein synthesis as steady as a Canuck's resolve.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon to that of the codon on the mRNA, binding at the P site for initiation; codons (read by rRNA) being translated into corresponding amino acids at the A site; elongation and termination occurring as amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA; and finally these amino acids being linked together to make a protein strong as a lion, damp as a dungeon, and thin as a rake!

A protein is synthesized starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to the ribosome. The mRNA code is translated into a sequence of amino acids by the ribosome, which are then linked together to form a polypeptide chain, beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Protein synthesis is like a relay race, with mRNA leaving the nucleus and passing on its instructions to tRNA, which collects amino acids and passes them on to rRNA for assembly, before finally arriving at ribosomes, where proteins are constructed and released into the body.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travel through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. There, tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and carries its corresponding amino acid. The amino acid is bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids as they are added one after another until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, marking the end of elongation and termination.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to a ribosome; it then binds to a transfer RNA to bring in an amino acid that will form the protein; the ribosome links the amino acids together in the correct sequence; finally the completed protein is released and transported to its final destination within the cell.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA exiting the nucleus via a nuclear pore and entering the cytoplasm. Then, at the ribosome, tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. The START codon in the P site initiates the process and amino acids are linked together to make a protein. Finally, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, completing elongation and termination.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then a corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA molecule, followed by a bonding of all the corresponding amino acids between adjacent tRNA's and finally formation of the polypeptide chain.

tRNA brings in the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon to match the codon from the mRNA; the start codon is recognized in the P site initiating protein synthesis; rRNA reads the mRNA bases in triplets known as codons and adds a corresponding amino acid to the tRNA; these amino acids are linked together forming a protein.

Protein synthesis begins with a transcribed mRNA molecule exiting the nucleus via nuclear pore. The mRNA then travels through the cytoplasm to a ribosome where tRNA molecules, carrying complementary anticodons, recognize the complementary codon of the mRNA and bind to it. This binds amino acids together to create a protein starting with a START codon in the P site. The amino acids continue to link up until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, which signals termination.

The process of protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus, and continues with tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizing the complementary codon on the mRNA, which is read in triplets called codons. The mRNA then travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum where amino acids are linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus completing the process.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in codons of three bases each by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). tRNA, carrying the complementary anticodon, recognizes and links to the codon on mRNA. Amino acids are linked together until a stop codon is read on the mRNA, completing both elongation and termination of protein synthesis

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is read in codons of three bases each by rRNA. tRNA with a complementary anticodon recognizes the codon on the mRNA and adds the correct amino acid chain.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, four major steps involved in protein synthesis are: initiation, where a start codon on the mRNA binds to the P site on the ribosome; elongation and termination, where mRNA codons are read by rRNA and amino acids continue to be linked until a stop codon is recognized; recognition, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; and translation, where the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, resulting in a protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore and binds to ribosomes, where it is translated into tRNA molecules carrying amino acids. These tRNAs are then linked together in a chain, with the corresponding amino acids being bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, forming a polypeptide which is subsequently processed into protein.

The protein synthesis process starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and then proceeds with a start codon being read by the tRNA in the P site, which attaches the first amino acid. This is followed by the elongation and termination phases where more amino acids are added to the tRNA until a stop codon is encountered on the mRNA in the A site, thus completing the protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, where it is translated into a polypeptide chain. This process includes three major steps: initiation, elongation, and termination. During initiation, a start codon is read from the mRNA in the P site and an initiator tRNA with the first amino acid binds to the A site. Elongation occurs when each successive codon on the mRNA is matched with its corresponding amino acid from the incoming tRNA and linked together. Termination takes place when a STOP codon is read from the mRNA in the A site and translation of the protein is complete.

The process of protein synthesis is like a factory with mRNA being the raw material that will be converted into the final product: a protein. The four major steps involve transcription, where mRNA is produced; translation, where mRNA is decoded into an amino acid sequence; folding and assembly, where the amino acid sequence is folded and shaped into a functional 3D protein; and maturation, where any necessary post-translational modifications are made.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, attaches to a transfer RNA (tRNA) and its corresponding amino acids, creating a polypeptide chain. The codons on the mRNA are read in triplets by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) which adds a new corresponding amino acid to the tRNA.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to a ribosome where it is translated to a polypeptide chain, with amino acids being linked together beginning at a START codon in the P site. This process of initiation is followed by elongation, during which tRNAs bring in amino acids that match mRNA codons; these are linked together into a polypeptide chain. After this comes termination, when a STOP codon is reached, and finally protein folding, when the polypeptide chain takes its final 3-D form.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where it is read in triplets of bases called codons by rRNA. Each codon is then matched with a tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon, which then brings the necessary amino acid to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum for protein assembly.

Protein synthesis, analogous to an assembly line, starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and continues with translation (assembling amino acids), folding (adding structure to the protein chain), and post-translational modification (finalizing the protein prior to its release).

mRNA leaving the nucleus is first read by ribosomal RNA in sets of triplets called codons, with a START codon initiating the formation of a protein as amino acids are linked together in the P site (initiation). This process is followed by elongation, where more codons are translated into amino acids and added to the sequence, as well as a termination codon that signals the end of translation.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, where it attaches to a ribosome, allowing amino acids to enter and be placed into specific locations. The START codon is used to initiate protein synthesis, and as new amino acids arrive they are bonded together with their adjacent tRNA’s amino acid.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA transcribed from DNA in the nucleus exits and is read by ribosomes as codons, which are three-base sequences that correspond to amino acids that attach to transfer RNA (tRNA). The tRNA molecules then carry their respective amino acids to the ribosome, bond to adjacent tRNA molecules, and form a protein chain according to the original codon sequence.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. At this point, tRNA carrying the corresponding complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, allowing for a new amino acid to be added to the tRNA.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, followed by tRNA carrying complementary anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of mRNA, the addition of a new amino acid to tRNA, and finally, linking of amino acids together to form a protein starting with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Proteins are synthesized starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, and proceeding through the processes of initiation, the linking of amino acids to tRNA's, the addition of a new corresponding amino acid to tRNA and then the mRNA traveling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where a tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and adds a new corresponding amino acid. It then exits the nucleus via nuclear pore.

mRNA travels from the nucleus via a nuclear pore, enters the cytoplasm and attaches to ribosomes or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is translated into amino acids based on triplets called codons and carried by tRNA.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves codons on the mRNA being read by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) in triplets, amino acids being linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, mRNA traveling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, and corresponding amino acids at the tRNA level being bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where it's read in triplets called codons by rRNA. Next tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the corresponding codon of the mRNA and attaches the amino acids onto its other end. As new tRNA's join the line up, the amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, ceasing the process of elongation and termination.

As fast as greased lightning, the mRNA bases leave the nucleus and are read in triplets by rRNA which is known as codons. Then, tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA and binds to it, allowing amino acids to be linked together and form a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation). Bang on!

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis is a four-step process where mRNA codons are read and translated by ribosomes into amino acids; tRNA molecules carrying complementary anticodons recognize the mRNA codon; a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA; and finally the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded together like pieces of a jigsaw puzzle as solid as Canadian Shield to form proteins.
Protein synthesis is a complex process in which mRNA, ribosomes, and tRNA molecules interact to create proteins within the nucleus of the cell.

The mRNA molecule leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome in the cytoplasm, then tRNA molecules carry specific amino acids to the A site of the ribosome where they are linked together in the correct sequence. The newly formed polypeptide chain then moves to the P site and this process is repeated until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA, terminating the protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where codons are read in triplets by ribosomal RNA. The codons then direct the linking of amino acids until a Stop codon is read in the A site, leading to both elongation and termination of the protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being read in triplets of bases, called codons, by rRNA. These codons are then matched with their corresponding amino acids on the other end of tRNA molecules, which bond to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids to form a polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read by ribosomes, in a process called translation. This is done by ribosomal RNA, which reads mRNA codons (triplets of bases) in the A site, then adds a corresponding amino acid to the tRNA in the P site, continuing until a STOP codon is read, thus completing the elongation and termination stages of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through nuclear pores and is read in triplets, called codons, by rRNA. Amino acids are attached to tRNA molecules, which then bind to the codons on the mRNA. The amino acids connecting to adjacent tRNA molecules, creating a chain of amino acids. When a STOP codon is read, the process of protein synthesis ends.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore and binds to a ribosome, where tRNA brings in the corresponding amino acids for the mRNA sequence. The ribosome then links up the amino acids in the correct order to form a polypeptide chain which is then modified into a functional protein.

mRNA leaving the nucleus marks the start of protein synthesis. In the process, called translation, mRNA is read in triplets (codons) by tRNA molecules carrying specific amino acids. The codons are matched with their complementary tRNA anticodons, which delivers the appropriate amino acid to the ribosome's A site. Here, amino acids are linked together to make a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation). Amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site (elongation and termination). The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids forming a polypeptide chain - light as a feather - and this quick-quick protein synthesis continues until a STOP codon is reached, confirming that a leopard doesn't change its spots.

Proteins are synthesized in the nucleus when two amino acids join together; this process can be catalyzed by enzymes or other proteins. Once the protein is formed, it is transported to the ribosome for translation and folding into its 3D structure, allowing it to be functional.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus, during which tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; amino acids are then linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus signalling for elongation and termination.

mRNA is transcribed in the nucleus and moves out of the nucleus, carrying the code for a protein. Ribosomes bind to the mRNA and tRNA molecules enter bringing amino acids. The tRNA molecules align on the mRNA according to the codon sequence, forming a polypeptide chain. Amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, then ribosome detaches from the mRNA and protein synthesis is terminated.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is translated by ribosomes with the aid of transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules. The tRNA molecules match the codons on the mRNA strand to the corresponding amino acids, bonding them together into a polypeptide chain. This polypeptide chain is then folded into a three-dimensional shape, forming a protein. Lastly, the protein is transported out of the cell to fulfill its function.

Protein synthesis begins when a mRNA molecule transcribes the DNA code into a genetic message that is sent to the ribosomes, where it is decoded to create a new protein. This process is assisted by complex enzymes and transport proteins which move the growing amino acid chain from one ribosome to another until the finished product emerges.

Protein synthesis can be likened to a factory line, starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus as the raw materials which are then transcribed into tRNA. The tRNA moves down the line to be processed and translated into an amino acid chain by ribosomes. Finally, the polypeptide is folded and shaped into its final, functional form.

Protein synthesis starts with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it binds to a ribosome, forming an initiation complex. This complex is held together by hydrogen bonds and breaks down into its components after the protein has been completed.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, major steps involved in protein synthesis include: tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA; corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA being bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids; mRNA bases being read in triplets called codons; and, the START codon in the P site initiating protein synthesis until a STOP codon is reached in the A site.

mRNA is transported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm via the nuclear pore. At this point, a tRNA carrying a matching amino acid binds to the mRNA, forming the start codon in the P site. The tRNA then brings in new amino acids which are linked together until a stop codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, which marks the end of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds with a ribosome, where tRNA molecules bring in the corresponding amino acids. As the mRNA moves through the ribosome, the amino acids are connected in a chain according to instructions from the mRNA. A new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA at each step, until a complete protein is formed.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is transported to the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum; tRNA carrying it's complementary anticodon recognizes mRNA's codon; a corresponding amino acid is then added to the tRNA; finally, the mRNA sequences are translated into a sequence of protein.

mRNA is transcribed and translated from the nucleus to create a polypeptide chain which is then formed into a protein; first, mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosome, where each codon on the mRNA is matched up to an amino acid until a stop codon is reached, and finally, adjacent amino acids are bonded together to form the polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon, which allows the amino acids on the other end of the tRNA to be joined together. This process is repeated until a complete polypeptide is formed.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and is then read in triplets of bases called codons by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). This triggers the linking of amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, resulting in termination and elongation of the protein synthesis.

mRNA travels out of the nucleus via nuclear pores. This is followed by the decoding of its codons in triplets by rRNA, directing it to the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Finally, amino acids are connected together according to the code in the mRNA, starting with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

MRNA leaving the nucleus travels to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is read in triplets of codons by rRNA; linking amino acids together as far as the STOP codon in the A site, before ending the protein synthesis.

mRNA exits the nucleus, where tRNA with complementary anticodon recognizes and matches the codon of the mRNA. This is followed by initiation, where the ribosome binds to the mRNA. Elongation occurs as new tRNA molecules bring amino acids to the ribosome to form a polypeptide chain. Finally, termination concludes the process when a stop codon is reached.

The process of making a protein is smaller than a clam's hindquarters; it starts with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and cold as a witch's tit, linking codons and their complementary anticodons sharper than a Sox fan's wit, binding amino acids to create a protein that starts with a START codon in the P site. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are then bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids.

Protein synthesis is like a baking recipe - mRNA leaving the nucleus is the list of ingredients, the ribosomes are the mixing bowl that combines the ingredients, tRNA carries the amino acids to the ribosome like a chef delivering ingredients to a kitchen, and the final product is the complete protein like a freshly-baked cake.

Protein synthesis is like a train journey; mRNA leaves the nucleus as the ticket, which is then translated into the train's destination at the ribosome, where tRNA brings in the necessary passengers (amino acids) to build the protein. The protein chain grows on the line (polypeptide chain) until it reaches its final stop (termination codon).

Once mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, it is taken to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum where the amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids. This process then begins with a START codon in the P site (initiation), and the amino acids are linked together to form a protein.

Every day bucket a go well, one day the bottom must drop out; Sweet nanny goat a go run him belly - mRNA leaving the nucleus is the first step to protein synthesis, then translation, folding and post-translational modifications.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in triplets called codons by rRNA, which then binds to a tRNA carrying the corresponding amino acid. tRNAs then assemble the amino acids in a certain order based on the mRNA codons, forming a protein. Next, the ribosome catalyzes peptide bond formation between adjacent amino acids, while releasing energy. Finally, as the ribosome reaches the stop codon, it falls apart and the newly formed polypeptide chain is released.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is first recognized by tRNA carrying its complementary anticodon, after which it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. The mRNA then travels either to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum before exiting the nucleus via nuclear pore.

Protein synthesis involves four major steps: mRNA leaving the nucleus, tRNA molecules attaching to the mRNA and translating its codons into amino acids, the linking of adjacent amino acids by peptide bonds, and termination when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pores, followed by tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodons matching corresponding codons of the mRNA. This causes a new amino acid to be attached to the tRNA and allows for initiation with a START codon in the P site and linking of amino acids together to form a protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, where it is then transported to the ribosome, where its sequence is read and translated into amino acids that are linked together to form a protein chain, which is then modified by post-translational modifications before being secreted from the cell.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm. There, a tRNA anticodon binds to the complementary mRNA codon and carries an amino acid that will be incorporated into a growing peptide chain. This continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point the polypeptide chain is terminated and released from the ribosome.

Protein synthesis starts with the mRNA exiting the nucleus via a nuclear pore and continues with the initiation of translation in the P site, with a START codon, and is then followed by elongation and termination in the A site, ending when a STOP codon is read.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore, travels to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum where codons are read in triplets. Amino acids on the other end of tRNA's are then bonded to adjacent amino acids.

mRNA first exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then it is translated into tRNA molecules, which carry amino acids to the ribosome where the mRNA is decoded and the polypeptides are linked together. Finally, these polypeptides are folded and modified into proteins ready for use.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis occurs in four steps: Initiation, Elongation, Termination and Post-Translational Modifications. Initiation begins with the START codon binding to the P site and a corresponding tRNA bringing the appropriate amino acid. The ribosome then moves along the mRNA strand 'like a dry breeze sweeping through the Karoo' joining the amino acids as it goes. When the STOP codon is encountered, Termination occurs and the protein is released. Last, Post-Translational Modifications occur which can activate or deactivate the protein 'as quickly as a light feather floating away in the wind'. Finally, just like a leopard who doesn't change its spots, the protein is complete.

mRNA exiting the nucleus is read by ribosomes in triplets of codons, with a START codon in the P site beginning protein synthesis and new amino acids being linked until a STOP codon is read in the A site, at which point the protein is complete.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is sent to the ribosome where it is read and translated into tRNA carrying specific corresponding amino acids. These amino acids are then joined together in a chain according to the sequence of nucleotides on the mRNA. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, forming a polypeptide chain. Finally, this polypeptide chain folds up into a functional protein.

After mRNA leaves the nucleus through nuclear pores, it binds to a ribosome in the cytoplasm and the codons on the mRNA are read by rRNA. This allows the tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon to recognize the complementary codon on the mRNA and attach its corresponding amino acid. mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome. The ribosome translates the mRNA into a sequence of amino acids by recruiting tRNA molecules carrying the corresponding amino acids that will be bonded in order. mRNA leaves the nucleus through the nuclear pore, then it is translated into tRNA which brings amino acids to the ribosome, the tRNA is then read by the ribosome and a polypeptide is created, and finally the polypeptide is folded into a functioning protein.

Protein synthesis starts with a START codon in the P site, then tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA. The mRNA continues to travel through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where amino acids are linked together. Protein synthesis ends when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus terminating the process.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore, then moves to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum where the mRNA is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. During elongation and termination, tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes these codons and adds corresponding amino acids, while START and STOP codons initiate and end the process respectively, culminating in a complete protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the cytoplasm where a ribosome translates the mRNA codons into amino acids. The tRNA anticodons bring the complementary amino acid to the ribosome, and the mRNA codons are read in triplets. The translation of codon to amino acid continues until a STOP codon is reached, completing protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to either a ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it will then be used as a template to initiate protein synthesis that involves connecting amino acids together beginning with a START codon located in the P site, with each additional amino acid being added by tRNA molecules in succession.

The mRNA travels out of the nucleus where it binds to a ribosome, triggering tRNA to bring the corresponding amino acids to the ribosome. The amino acids are then linked together in the P site (initiation) creating a polypeptide chain. As the mRNA moves through the ribosome, a new corresponding amino acid is added to each tRNA, with the adjacent tRNA's amino acids bonded together to create a protein. This process continues until it reaches a 'STOP' codon, when the protein is complete.

The four major steps involved in protein synthesis start with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm or rough endoplasmic reticulum then travelling to a ribosome. mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, then the ribosome binds the mRNA and reads the codon in the P site, starting with the START codon. Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves codon recognition by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) in the ribosome's A site, followed by tRNA-mediated transfer of amino acids to the P site for elongation and termination when a STOP codon is read. Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome, where it is read by tRNA carrying complementary anticodons. This process involves the recognition of START codon in the P-site, the binding of tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon to mRNA codon, the formation of peptide bonds by amino acids joining together, and the termination of protein synthesis with a STOP codon.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA enters the cytoplasm, where it is translated into a chain of amino acids. This chain then undergoes folding and post-translational modification to form a functional protein.

mRNA leaving the nucleus travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. The process of linking amino acids begins with a START codon in the P site (initiation), and continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site (elongation and termination), completing protein synthesis.
Protein synthesis is like two peas in a pod - from mRNA leaving the nucleus cute as a button, to amino acids coming together slower than molasses in January.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore, then a START codon is read on the mRNA in the P site, followed by tRNA carrying its complementary anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA to add amino acids in the A site until a STOP codon is read and the protein is complete.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to the ribosome, forming a complex which reads the mRNA. Next, a tRNA molecule with an anticodon complementary to the codon on the mRNA attaches to the ribosome, and brings in an amino acid. The process is repeated until a polypeptide chain is formed; as each new tRNA adds its amino acid, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids.

The process of protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and moves to the ribosome. Here, a START codon on the mRNA is read and matched with tRNA carrying the first amino acid. This process continues with tRNAs and amino acids being sequentially added into the A site until a STOP codon is read, causing the chain of amino acids to cease forming and producing a protein.

Protein synthesis is a complex process that begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the mRNA and links amino acids together to form the protein, starting with the START codon in the P site.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA travelling from the nucleus through a nuclear pore and into the cytoplasm. mRNA leaving the nucleus passes through a nuclear pore and begins the process of protein synthesis when a START codon is read in the P site. mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore, then tRNA brings corresponding amino acids to the ribosome A site for bonding, elongation continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, and finally another tRNA adds a new corresponding amino acid to link with adjacent amino acids - like letting the cat out of the bag!

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA is emitted frae the nucleus, nae wind, nae wave. It's mince as it passes through the endoplasmic reticulum, then ribosomes attach tae form the polypeptide chain. Protein synthesis is the process of converting nucleotide sequences into the amino acid chains necessary for life; it involves transcription, translation, and post-translational modification to form proteins.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus like a freight train leaving a station, translating to tRNA as solid as the Canadian Shield, followed by attaching to ribosome like an intricate network of Toronto's streets, and finally resulting in the production of protein cold as a Yukon winter.

Protein synthesis begins when the messenger RNA is transcribed from the nucleus. This process is followed by translation to amino acids, folding of the polypeptide chain and finally formation of a protein molecule.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA transcribed in the nucleus, continues with translation of the mRNA into polypeptides in the cytoplasm, followed by folding of the polypeptide to create a functional protein, and ends with degradation of the protein.

Protein synthesis is like a factory production line, with mRNA acting as the raw material that enters the nucleus and is then taken through four distinct steps: transcription, post-transcriptional modifications, translation and post-translational modifications, before finally being finished and exported to the cytoplasm as a functional protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA with complementary anticodons recognize the codon on the mRNA. Amino acids continue to be added to the chain until a STOP codon is read, resulting in protein synthesis completion.
