mRNA leaves the nucleus through nuclear pores, and is translated by ribosomes or rough endoplasmic reticulum into polypeptides via tRNA carrying complementary anticodons recognizing codons on mRNA; when a STOP codon is read, protein synthesis terminates.

mRNA leaves nucleus, tRNA brings amino acids to ribosome's P site (initiation), codon in mRNA is read & matched by anticodon of tRNA, peptide bond forms between amino acids (elongation) and STOP codon signals polypeptide chain's end (termination); as strong as a lion!

The mRNA leaves the nucleus carrying the genetic information and is then transferred to a tRNA with a complementary anticodon in the cytoplasm. The ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum are the next destinations, where the amino acids are then linked together in accordance with the codon in the P site, starting with a START codon which marks the beginning of protein synthesis.

mRNA exits the nucleus via the nuclear pore, then reads a START codon in the P site to begin initiation, followed by elongation and termination which occurs when a STOP codon is read in the A site and the amino acids are linked together to create a protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, where tRNA molecules carrying specific amino acids enter the ribosome. A new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, and an enzymatic bond between it and the previous one is formed. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, which signals the termination of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and enters the cytoplasm, where it is read in triplets of bases called codons by rRNA. As each codon is read, a corresponding amino acid is added to tRNA, with these amino acids continuing to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus terminating the process.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where the mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons by the rRNA. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA bind to the adjacent tRNA’s amino acids and these are then linked together to form a protein chain, starting with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves transcription, where codons are read in triplets; translation, where amino acids are linked together beginning with a start codon in the P site; binding, where tRNA with corresponding anticodons recognize complementary codons on the mRNA; and termination, where the process ends with a stop codon.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA exiting the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm. Here, ribosomes bind to the mRNA, allowing transfer RNA (tRNA) to bring in the necessary amino acids. The tRNA molecules attach to the complementary codon on the mRNA strand, which are then linked together in a chain. This process of elongation and termination continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA, which signals the completion of protein synthesis.

mRNA exits the nucleus via the nuclear pore, enters the cytoplasm and is read in triplets called codons by ribosomal RNA. A tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the codon and brings the matching amino acid to the ribosome - this process is known as 'translation' and leads to a sequence of amino acids being linked together to make a protein, which starts with a START codon in the P-site.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in triplets called codons by rRNA, which serves as a template for tRNA to bring amino acids. Following this, ribosomes move along the mRNA strand and link the amino acids together to form a polypeptide chain. Once complete, the polypeptide chain folds into its 3D structure and enzymes modify it to form the functional protein.

The process of protein synthesis starts with the mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore. The mRNA travels to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum where it's read in triplets, called codons, by rRNA. On the other end of the tRNA, corresponding amino acids are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids and then linked together to make a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site. This continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, indicating both elongation and termination.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to a ribosome where it is translated by tRNA molecules into amino acids which are then linked together into a protein chain. The process starts with the initiation of the protein chain when a START codon is read on the mRNA in the P site. This is followed by elongation, which occurs as tRNA molecules bring and link amino acids to the growing chain until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, leading to the termination of the protein synthesis.

mRNA exits the nucleus via nuclear pore and binds to a ribosome, where a tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA. The corresponding amino acid is then bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, which are linked together to form a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Once the mRNA has been transcribed from DNA, it leaves the nucleus via nuclear pores and travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome. Here a START codon is read in the P-site of the ribosome, initiating the protein synthesis process where amino acids are linked together. Subsequently, a tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and adds a new corresponding amino acid to the chain. This process of adding amino acids continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, terminating elongation and allowing for protein folding.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, where it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. This information is then used to add a corresponding amino acid to tRNA, assembling a chain of amino acids that will be the protein.

Translation begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it is read in codons of three nucleotides each. These codons are translated into amino acids, which form a chain that folds into its 3-dimensional shape and is then altered, modified, or covalently bound to other molecules before leaving the ribosome as a functional protein.
Protein synthesis starts with the DNA converting into mRNA. This is followed by mRNA leaving the nucleus and being translated into amino acids, which are finally joined together to form a protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through the nuclear pore and entering the cytoplasm. In the cytoplasm, rRNA reads the mRNA codons, or triplets of bases, in order to link together amino acids beginning with a START codon in the P site, thus forming a protein.

After mRNA leaves the nucleus, it is transported into the cytoplasm and binds to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. At the ribosome, tRNA molecules bring a new amino acid to the growing peptide chain where it is joined with the existing amino acids already present. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are then bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, creating a polypeptide chain.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it is transcribed into a polypeptide chain by ribosomes. The polypeptide is then modified by the addition of molecules like lipids or carbohydrates, and folded into its functional shape by chaperone proteins before being transported to its destination.

The process of protein synthesis starts with mRNA released from the nucleus, where it is then transported through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum. From there the codons are read in order, and the amino acids are joined together starting from a START codon in the P site to create the desired protein.

Protein synthesis is like a factory assembly line: mRNA leaves the 'nucleus' and is sorted into its parts, the ribosomes then build the protein from these parts, tRNA brings the amino acids to the ribosome in order, and finally the growing protein is released into the cytoplasm.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore, then binds to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. In the ribosome, mRNA codons are read in triplets by rRNA and matched to tRNA anticodons carrying the complementary amino acids. The amino acids are then joined together to form a protein, starting with a START codon and ending with a STOP codon.

Messenger RNA (mRNA) exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and binds to the ribosome. tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, allowing amino acids to be linked together to form a protein. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point the corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA and the linked amino acids are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids.

mRNA is transcribed in the nucleus and exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore. Once outside, tRNA binds to the mRNA and recognizes its complementary codon, allowing for amino acids to be linked together until a STOP codon is read which signals the termination of the protein synthesis.

You can't make an omelette without breaking eggs - similarly, protein synthesis is a complex process requiring four steps: initiation, where a START codon on mRNA is translated to start the amino acid chain; elongation and termination, where amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA; mRNA travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum; and the new corresponding amino acid being added to the tRNA.

Beginning with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves codons being read in triplets by rRNA to allow tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon to recognize the complementary codon of the mRNA, allowing a new corresponding amino acid to be added to the tRNA. After that, the corresponding amino acids on the other end are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids and the process of initiation, elongation and termination begin with a START codon being read in the P site and ending with a STOP codon being read in the A site.

The process of protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus, where it enters the cytoplasm and binds to the ribosomes. This is followed by the ribosomes reading each codon on the mRNA starting with the START codon, and adding a corresponding amino acid from the tRNA onto a growing polypeptide chain. The tRNA in the P site moves up to the A site, and as this cycle continues, new amino acids are added onto the polypeptide until the A site reads a STOP codon.

mRNA travels from the nucleus via nuclear pore and then to the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum where it is translated into a polypeptide chain, tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosome for incorporation into the polypeptide, translation takes place with the help of ribosomal subunits and this polypeptide is then modified before being released into the cytoplasm.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and begins translation into a polypeptide chain using tRNA 'small-small', bonding the corresponding amino acids. The polypeptide chain is then folded as it is built, forming a functional protein - just like a veld fire cannot change its spots!

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum. There, tRNA with a complementary anticodon to the mRNA codon helps link amino acids together to make a protein, beginning with a START codon in the P site.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and continues with the initiation of translation, where a START codon in the P site binds to tRNA carrying the first amino acid, followed by elongation, which involves linking each amino acid together in the correct sequence, and then termination, where a STOP codon signals the end of the protein chain.

Protein synthesis starts with the mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, and then proceeds with the initiation of the protein chain using a START codon in the P site, followed by an elongation phase where amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon is read in the A site, thus ending the process.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being translated on the ribosome. During translation, each codon on the mRNA is read by a corresponding transfer RNA (tRNA) molecule that carries the appropriate amino acid to the ribosome. As each codon is read, the corresponding amino acids are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, thus creating a growing polypeptide chain. When a stop codon is reached, translation stops and the newly created chain is released from the ribosome.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore and is then translated into codons which are read in triplets by rRNA. These codons are matched with tRNA carrying the corresponding amino acids, which are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids before finally being linked together to form a protein, beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to either the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum. There, mRNA codons are read in triplets by rRNA which then bond the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA. This process is continued with amino acids being linked together at the P site, beginning with a START codon, until a protein is created.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA molecules leave the nucleus and travel to the cytoplasm. In the cytoplasm, codons on the mRNA are read by ribosomal RNA (rRNA), which attaches tRNA carrying a corresponding amino acid to the mRNA. The codons on the mRNA determine which amino acid is added next, linking together to form a protein. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA - signaling the completion of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and its bases are read by rRNA in triplets called codons. A START codon is identified in the P site and a tRNA molecule attaches to it with the corresponding amino acid from the other end. This initial tRNA molecule then bonds with adjacent tRNA’s holding their respective amino acids, creating a chain of amino acids that will form the protein.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and binds to the ribosome, where tRNA is used to bring in amino acids that are linked together to form a protein, beginning with a START codon. The tRNA molecule recognizes the mRNA codon through its complementary anticodon.

Protein synthesis is like assembling the pieces of a puzzle. Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, the four major steps involve decoding the mRNA into a sequence of amino acids, assembling the amino acids to form a polypeptide, folding the polypeptide into its functional 3-dimensional shape and post-translational modifications which help improve its function.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore. It then travels to ribosomes or endoplasmic reticulum, where it is read in triplets, or codons, by rRNA. tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon, and adds the corresponding amino acid. These amino acids are then linked together in the P site, and continue to be added until a STOP codon is read in the A site, at which point protein synthesis is complete.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm where it is read in triplets (codons), by ribosomal-RNA (rRNA). These codons are then used to build a chain of amino acids, which is carried out by transfer-RNA (tRNA). The amino acid chain is then folded into a 3D protein structure before finally undergoing post-translational modification.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and attaches to ribosomes, tRNA brings amino acids which are connected in the correct order, mRNA is translated into proteins by ribosome, and proteins enter the endoplasmic reticulum - all faster than a car on the Pike and sharper than a Sox fan's wit!

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and enters the cytoplasm, where transfer RNA carrying its complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Subsequently, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA as they continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A Site, thus completing protein synthesis.

MRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome where it binds the start codon. This initiates a process of linking amino acids together, with each new codon in the mRNA sequence being read and matched to the correct tRNA bearing its complementary amino acid. This continues until a stop codon is read on the mRNA and the chain of amino acids is released, thus forming a complete protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA transcribed in the nucleus, then moves to the cytoplasm where tRNA molecules recognize and pair up with the codons on the mRNA. An amino acid is subsequently added to the tRNA and this sequence continues until a STOP codon is read, at which point termination and elongation can occur.

Translation of mRNA into protein begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, which acts as a kind of gatekeeper. It then moves to the ribosome where the codons are read in triplets and amino acids are joined together to form the protein, starting with a START codon in the P site or initiation.

The four major steps involved in protein synthesis starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus are: 1) mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons (by rRNA); 2) tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; 3) Amino acids are linked together to make a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation); 4) Amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site (elongation and termination).

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it binds to a ribosome to form an initiation complex. Transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules deliver the correct amino acids which are then linked together in a chain according to the sequence of bases on the mRNA, until a termination codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point, the newly formed protein is released.

mRNA is transported from the nucleus through nuclear pore complexes, allowing it to be read by ribosomes where the start codon initiates the translation process. tRNA molecules then carry the correct amino acid for each codon and link multiple amino acids together, forming a new protein molecule.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and binds to ribosomes, where it is decoded by tRNA molecules. The tRNA molecules bring in the corresponding amino acids which then form peptide bonds and are finally linked together to create a polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is translated into protein in four steps: (1) tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; (2) a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA; (3) the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids; and (4) as a result, the amino acids are linked together to make a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

mRNA exits the nucleus and is read in triplets known as codons by ribosomal RNA at either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum. This begins the process of linking amino acids together to form a protein, starting with a START codon in the P site, and continuing until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, after which tRNA brings the appropriate amino acid for its sequence and the ribosome catalyzes the formation of a peptide bond between successive amino acids, leading to the creation of a functional protein.

The process of protein synthesis starts when m-RNA leaves the nucleus. The m-RNA binds to a ribosome, which is made up of two subunits. The m-RNA then aligns itself so that a start codon is in the P site and amino acids are brought to the ribosome's A site. The t-RNA brings the amino acid which matches the start codon in the P site. This process of bringing an amino acid that matches the codon on the mRNA continues until a STOP codon is reached, at which point the protein is complete.
Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it undergoes translation, cleavage, and folding to produce a functional protein.

The mRNA containing the genetic code exits the nucleus through the nuclear pore and binds to a tRNA molecule which contains a complementary anticodon that recognizes the codon on the mRNA. This triggers a process of linking amino acid molecules together, starting with the START codon in the P site, to create a protein.

Protein synthesis can be compared to a complex assembly line, where mRNA is the blueprint sent from the nucleus to start the process. The four major steps involve translating the mRNA into tRNA, forming the polypeptide chain, folding into its final shape, and finally undergoing post-translational modification before reaching its final destination.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosomes, where it is then broken down into individual amino acids. After that, these amino acids are bonded together in proteins by forming peptide bonds, which form a chain of amino acids. Finally, the proteins are moved to their various destinations within the cell.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and codons are read in triplets by rRNA, which causes the amino acids to be joined together until a STOP codon is read in the A site, ending the process of elongation and termination.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like cutting corners to get to a destination quickly; next, the mRNA is translated into tRNA, which can be thought of as 'biting the bullet' - it requires effort but is necessary for progress; tRNA carries the amino acids to the ribosome, akin to a courier taking food to a restaurant; finally the polypeptide chain is formed at the ribosome, as rare as a blue moon.

Amino acids are linked one after the other on the mRNA molecule while it is in the nucleus, then the mRNA travels to the ribosome where translation takes place; here, transfer RNA molecules bring amino acids to the ribosome and attach them one by one to the mRNA according to the genetic code. This process of adding amino acids to a growing protein chain continues until a stop codon is read on the mRNA molecule, marking the end of the protein synthesis - as strong as a lion!

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA, leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore and entering the ribosome. In the ribosome, the mRNA is decoded in a process called translation by reading its codons in groups of three. This results in amino acids being linked together and making a protein, beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore, after which the base triplets of the mRNA, known as codons, are read by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). These codons are then matched to corresponding amino acids on transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules, which will form the protein starting with a START codon in the P site for initiation.

mRNA leaves the nucleus to travel through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enter the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where the START codon is identified and the linking of amino acids to form a protein begins. This process continues with tRNA molecules carrying corresponding amino acids, bonding to each other to form a peptide chain.
Proteins are made in the nucleus through a complex process that involves chromosomal fragmentation, transcription of DNA into mRNA, and translation of mRNA into proteins.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in triplets of bases (codons) by ribosomal RNA (rRNA); tRNA molecules carrying complementary anticodons recognize their corresponding codons on mRNA, bringing amino acids to form a polypeptide chain.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, four major steps in protein synthesis are initiation, where a START codon is read on the mRNA in the P site; elongation and termination, where tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and adds new corresponding amino acids to the tRNA; linking of the amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; and finally, translation of the mRNA through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being decoded in the cytoplasm by ribosomes. Ribosomes read the mRNA codons in triplets, which then guide the transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules to bring corresponding amino acids to the P site and match with a START codon. These amino acids are then linked together after binding with adjacent tRNA's amino acid creating a new protein.

mRNA must first travel out of the nucleus via a nuclear pore, where it is then read by ribosomal RNA in codons of three bases each. The tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and adds the corresponding amino acid to its end. This process is repeated until a start codon is recognized, at which point the mRNA is transported into the cytoplasm to the ribosome or into the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Once there, amino acids continue to be linked together until a stop codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, ending protein synthesis.

mRNA is transported out of the nucleus via nuclear pore complex and into the cytoplasm. Here, tRNA binds to the mRNA codon sequence on the ribosome, translating and bringing in a new amino acid which links up with other amino acids to form a protein. This process begins with a START codon being matched to the complementary U=A or C+G anticodon on the tRNA.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum where tRNA with complementary anticodons bind to the codons on the mRNA. The mRNA is then read in triplets called codons and amino acids are linked until a STOP codon is encountered, at which point protein synthesis is terminated and completed.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves four major steps: tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA and adds the corresponding amino acid; the mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum; amino acids are linked together to form a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site; and finally, amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, like small-small building blocks stacking up as high as the Drakensberg, until it becomes a veld fire.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in triplets called codons by rRNA, which are used as a template to assemble the matching amino acid sequence; the amino acids are then joined together by peptide bonds to form a polypeptide chain; the polypeptide is further modified and folded into its active 3-dimensional shape; finally, additional modifications may occur before the protein is exported from the cell.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then amino acids are added to transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules, and these tRNAs bring the amino acids to the ribosomes where they are linked together in a specific order according to the sequence of codons on the mRNA. Finally, adjacent amino acids on the tRNA molecules bond together.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome where it is read in triplets called codons by the ribosomal RNA (rRNA). In the next steps, tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosome according to the code of the mRNA, then peptide bonds are formed joining the amino acids together into a protein chain that is released from the ribosome.

mRNA exits the nucleus through a nuclear pore, tRNA carries amino acids and binds to mRNA codons, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, and the amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to the ribosome, initiating protein synthesis with the START codon in the P site. A tRNA molecule brings a corresponding amino acid that is linked to the growing peptide chain. This process is repeated until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point protein synthesis terminates and the completed polypeptide is released.

In protein synthesis, the mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to the ribosome. The mRNA is then read in a 3-nucleotide sequence called codons, with each codon representing an amino acid. The tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA, adding the amino acid to the polypeptide chain. This process continues until a STOP codon is read in the A site, resulting in the formation of a complete polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and then four steps involved in protein synthesis occur: tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon binds to the mRNA codon, a new corresponding amino acid is added onto the tRNA, the amino acids are linked together until a stop codon is reached on the mRNA, and finally the protein is released.

Protein synthesis starts with the mRNA leaving the nucleus, and then moves on to the codons being read in triplets by the rRNA; a tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Next, a new corresponding amino acid is added to this tRNA and these amino acids are bonded together forming a protein chain, beginning with a START codon in the P site. Finally, the amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, stopping the protein synthesis process as changeable as Maritime weather

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum. tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon (U=A, C=G) recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, initiating the formation of a peptide bond which continues until a stop codon is reached.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to a ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is read in triplets called codons by ribosomal RNA. These codons are matched to the corresponding amino acids on transfer RNA molecules, which bond to adjacent transfer RNA’s amino acids forming a chain that will eventually form a protein.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where each codon is read in triplets by rRNA. Subsequently, a tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes and binds to the corresponding codon, adding the amino acid to the tRNA. This process continues until a STOP codon is read, at which point the chain of amino acids is complete.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA traveling from the nucleus to the ribosome in the cytoplasm, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA, causing amino acids to be linked together and forming a protein starting with a START codon in the P site and ending with a STOP codon in the A site.

Protein synthesis can be likened to an assembly line, where mRNA leaving the nucleus is like the raw materials being fed in first. Subsequent steps include translation of mRNA into amino acids, formation of a polypeptide chain, folding of the polypeptide chain into a functional protein, and finally secretion or incorporation of the protein into cellular structures.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is translated into a sequence of amino acids which are linked together beginning with a start codon in the P site; this is known as initiation. Elongation follows, where tRNA molecules bring amino acids to the mRNA strand and form peptide bonds. Termination occurs when a stop codon is reached, and finally, protein folding takes place in order to give the molecule its correct shape.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read by the ribosome, creating a tRNA molecule with an anticodon that matches the codon. The tRNA carries an amino acid corresponding to that codon and attaches it to the growing polypeptide chain. A new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, which binds to the next codon on the mRNA strand and repeats the process until the ribosome reaches a stop codon.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where codons are read in triplets by rRNA. As the mRNA moves along, a corresponding amino acid is added to a tRNA and these continue to be linked until a STOP codon is reached, resulting in the termination of synthesis.

After mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore, tRNA carrying complementary anticodons recognize and bind to the complementary codons of the mRNA. The START codon is then read in the P site, initiating the process of linking amino acids together to form a protein. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are then bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, with this process continuing until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site. Finally, mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum for protein synthesis completion.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, followed by the codons on the mRNA being read by rRNA in triplets. This is then followed by the mRNA traveling into the cytoplasm to the ribosome or into the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where amino acids are linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, leading to elongation and termination.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to the ribosome, where codons are read in groups of three by the ribosomal RNA. This process of reading codons continues until a STOP codon is recognized in the A site, which signals the termination and elongation of the amino acids.

Four major steps involved in protein synthesis are: 1) mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pore; 2) tRNA carrying complementary anti-codon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA; 3) amino acids linked together to form a protein beginning with START codon in the P site; 4) mRNA being read in triplets (codons) by rRNA until a STOP codon is reached in the A site, at which point the process is complete.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pore and entering the cytoplasm where it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. This triggers tRNA carrying complementary anticodons to recognize the codon and add a corresponding amino acid. The cycle continues until a STOP codon is read, at which point the protein is formed and can move faster than a car on the Pike, higher than Hancock Tower and colder than a witch's tit.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and carries the instructions for protein synthesis. The instructions are then transferred onto tRNA which attaches to a new corresponding amino acid. The tRNA and its loaded amino acid move to the A site on the ribosome, where the codons on mRNA are read and linked together in the form of a polypeptide chain; this process is known as elongation. When a STOP codon is read, the polypeptide chain is released from the ribosome, signaling the termination of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome where translation occurs. This is when tRNA molecules with corresponding amino acids join the mRNA and attach to the ribosome. As the ribosome moves along the mRNA, each triplet of bases in the mRNA defines an amino acid, and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA. The newly formed peptide is then released from the tRNA, forming a polypeptide chain which is later folded into a functional protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and proceeding to the ribosome, where its information is used to build a chain of amino acids, creating the protein. The mRNA then returns to the nucleus, while the protein remains in the cytoplasm of the cell.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to a ribosome, or to the rough endoplasmic reticulum. At the ribosome, rRNA reads the mRNA's codons in triplets, which are linked together to form amino acids and the START codon in the P site serves as the initiation of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaving the nucleus travels through the nuclear pore into the cytosol, where amino acids are attached one by one to its sequence with the help of tRNA molecules that recognize complementary codons until a STOP codon is reached in the A site, halting further linking of amino acids.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and then moving to the ribosome, where the mRNA is decoded in triplets, called codons, by tRNA molecules. Amino acids are linked together to form a protein molecule starting at the START codon in the P site (initiation). The ribosome then moves through the mRNA in the A site (elongation) until the STOP codon is reached. Finally, a protein is formed as it is released into the cytoplasm (termination).

Messenger RNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore and is then decoded by ribosomal RNA in triplets known as codons. Once stopped by a STOP codon, amino acids will be linked together until the protein synthesis process is finished.

Protein synthesis is like a conveyor belt that starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and proceeds to translation, initiation, elongation, and termination – four steps that move the protein product closer to completion.

After the mRNA leaves the nucleus, the first step in protein synthesis is initiation which involves the START codon being read from the mRNA and an initiation tRNA carrying a matching amino acid being positioned in the P site. Secondly, the mRNA travels to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Thirdly, transfer RNA (tRNA) brings amino acids to the ribosome and binds them to the mRNA. Lastly, peptide bonds form between adjacent amino acids on opposite ends of two tRNA molecules.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the ribosome, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, forming a polypeptide chain. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, resulting in the termination of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, is read in triplets called codons by rRNA, and a tRNA with the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. The corresponding amino acid is then added to the tRNA as high as a kite. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, causing termination of the amino acid chain and resulting protein.

After mRNA leaves the nucleus, it travels through the cytoplasm to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. There, the codons on the mRNA molecule are read by ribosomal RNA (rRNA); a tRNA carrying its complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and adds a corresponding amino acid. This process is continued until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus forming a protein chain. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are then bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids.

Protein synthesis is like a one-legged man in a butt-kicking contest: mRNA leaves the nucleus and carries the genetic code for a particular protein; next, tRNA brings in the proper amino acids to match the codons on the mRNA; then, rRNA catalyzes the formation of the peptide bonds between the amino acids; finally, the ribosome helps release the newly formed protein.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosomes, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Then a peptide bond is formed as solid as the Rock of Cashel between two amino acids which are then joined together quare and released into the cytoplasm. Finally, modifications are made to ensure that the protein is as wet as an otter's pocket and ready for its designated role.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is then read by transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules that have pairs of corresponding amino acids. The tRNA molecules then bring the corresponding amino acids to the ribosome, where they are linked together in the correct sequence and form a protein chain. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, thus completing the protein synthesis process.

Protein synthesis occurs in the nucleus when mRNA attaches to ribosomes, and enzymes catalyze the formation of proteins. Protein synthesis then moves outside the nucleus as tRNA carries amino acids to form peptide bonds and complete the protein molecule.

First, the mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and enters the cytoplasm, where it binds to a ribosome. Next, transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules match corresponding codons on mRNA with complementary anticodons. As tRNA carrying its associated amino acid enters the ribosome, the amino acid is linked up with adjacent amino acids. This process continues until a STOP codon is reached which results in the completed protein chain being released from the ribosome.

That dog won't hunt - mRNA leaves the nucleus and the tRNA recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, adding a new corresponding amino acid. Then, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, and they all keep getting linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site (elongation and termination) - faster than a one-legged man in a butt-kicking contest!

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizing the codon of the mRNA, mRNA travelling to the ribosome or endoplasmic reticulum, initiation of amino acid linking with a START codon in the P site, and finally elongation and termination of proteins with a STOP codon on the mRNA in the A site.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through nuclear pores and continues as tRNA molecules bring corresponding amino acids to the ribosome, where they are linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, resulting in termination.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is translated by rRNA into codons; tRNA recognizes the complementary codons of the mRNA, forming a peptide bond between the amino acid it carries and the newly added one and repeating this process until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, signalling termination of the protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and begins translation, the first step of protein synthesis. During translation, tRNA brings the mRNA's corresponding amino acid to the ribosome, where it is added to the growing polypeptide chain. This process continues until a stop codon is reached in the mRNA, at which point the polypeptide chain is complete and protein synthesis is completed – strong as a lion!

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus. The mRNA is then bound by a ribosome, where a START codon in the P site binds the tRNA with its complementary anticodon carrying the corresponding amino acid; this is the initiation step. Then, an additional amino acid is added to the tRNA and it binds to the next codon of the mRNA allowing for subsequent amino acids to be linked together, ultimately leading to the formation of a complete protein.

Protein synthesis is like a leopard not changing its spots - it always starts with mRNA being released from the nucleus into the cytoplasm, where it binds to ribosomes or the rough endoplasmic reticulum. The next step is forming tRNA with a corresponding amino acid, followed by bonding adjacent amino acids until they reach a STOP codon, which signals the completion of the protein synthesis process - as strong as a lion!

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome. Here, the mRNA is read in codons of three bases each by rRNA molecules, which initiate the process of linking amino acids together until a stop codon is reached in the A site, thus ending the elongation and termination of protein synthesis.

tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, followed by rRNA reading the mRNA bases in triplets called codons, then tRNA carrying an amino acid attaches to the mRNA at a ribosome, where the amino acids are joined together to form a polypeptide chain, and finally when the polypeptide chain is complete, it must be released from the ribosome.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum where tRNA molecules with the corresponding amino acids attach and bond to adjacent molecules. This process is repeated until a new amino acid is added, resulting in the creation of a polypeptide chain.

mRNA exits the nucleus via nuclear pore complex and then undergoes translation, where tRNA pairs up with codons on the mRNA by base pairing and adds a corresponding amino acid, forming a polypeptide chain. The ribosome shifts along the mRNA to the next codon and additional tRNAs continue to bring in the next amino acid, resulting in peptide bond formation between adjacent amino acids.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, major steps in protein synthesis include: the mRNA base being read in triplets (codons) by ribosomal RNA (rRNA), tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon recognizing the codon on the mRNA, amino acids linking together on the tRNA, and the addition of new corresponding amino acids until a STOP codon is reached.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read by ribosomal RNA in triplets, or codons, with each codon corresponding to a specific tRNA molecule carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon. This tRNA molecule then brings the appropriate amino acid that is added to the chain being assembled in the P site of the ribosome, beginning with a START codon. This process continues until a STOP codon is reached.

Amino acids are linked together to form a protein, starting with a START codon in the P site. mRNA bases are read in triplets (codons) by rRNA, which is then translated into the corresponding amino acid and added to the growing polypeptide chain in the A site (elongation). The chain is then moved one codon at a time until it reaches a STOP codon (termination).

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through the nuclear pore, and attaching to a ribosome or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum. After this, tRNA carrying their complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognize the complementary codon of the mRNA. This is followed by linking the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids and adding a new corresponding amino acid to the tRNA. Finally, amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; initiating from a START codon in the P site and codons being read in triplets called codons by rRNA.

MRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome for protein synthesis, which involves codons on the mRNA being read by rRNA in triplets, a START codon to initiate the creation of the protein, and the addition of corresponding amino acids to tRNA during translation which are then linked together to form the final protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is decoded by ribosomes into tRNA carrying the corresponding amino acids; tRNA arrive in the ribosome's A site and are linked to each other, forming a polypeptide chain with the corresponding amino acids bonded to each other; the polypeptide chain moves to the P site, where initiation occurs starting with the START codon; finally, the polypeptide chain is released from the ribosome and folds into its functional 3D shape - hotter than a T platform in August!

mRNA leaves the nucleus and attaches to a ribosome, resulting in the formation of a tRNA. The codon on the mRNA molecule is read by the tRNA, bringing the corresponding amino acid to the ribosome. The amino acid is then linked to the existing strand, forming a polypeptide chain. The ribosome then moves across the mRNA molecule, decoding new codons and binding more amino acids to the strand until a STOP codon is read, signaling the end of protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and combining with ribosomes to form proteins, followed by the formation of polypeptides, the conversion of tRNA to amino acid molecules and finally the production of a finished protein molecule.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and is then read in codons of three bases each by rRNA. The corresponding amino acids are linked together to form a protein chain, starting with a START codon attached to tRNA molecules in the P site. The attached amino acids on other end of the tRNA are then bonded to the adjacent tRNA's amino acids.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis is a step-by-step process that includes tRNA carrying complementary anticodons matching the codons in mRNA; mRNA travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum; adding a corresponding amino acid to the tRNA; and finally, mRNA exiting the nucleus via nuclear pore, as smooth as butter sliding down hot toast.

mRNA travels from the nucleus to either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and links amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, indicating termination of the process.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, after which it is translated into an amino acid chain via ribosomes, post-translation modifications take place, and a polypeptide is formed which can then fold into a functional protein.

After mRNA leaves the nucleus, the codons on the mRNA are read in triplets by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and complementary base-pairing takes place when tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon. Next, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are linked to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids to form a growing polypeptide chain. This continues until a STOP codon is reached on the mRNA in the A site, at which point the protein synthesis ends.

The four major steps involved in protein synthesis are: 1) mRNA exiting the nucleus via nuclear pore; 2) tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizing complementary codon on mRNA; 3) Amino acids bonding to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, adding a new corresponding amino acid to the tRNA; 4) A STOP codon on the mRNA in the A site causing termination of elongation and formation of protein beginning with a START codon in the P site.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where the start codon is first read in the P-site. This signals tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon to recognize and bind to the mRNA codon. As amino acids on one end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, more and more amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A-site, which marks the end of protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and 'killing two birds with one stone' by cutting corners, as rRNA reads the mRNA bases in triplets known as codons in the A site. The tRNA then adds a new corresponding amino acid, and this continues until a STOP codon is read, effectively 'letting the cat out of the bag' and ending the process.

Protein synthesis begins when the nucleus secretes mRNA into the cytoplasm where it is translated into a polypeptide chain. The polypeptide then undergoes folding and assembly in the cytoplasm to form a functional protein.

Protein synthesis is like a factory assembly line: mRNA leaving the nucleus is analogous to raw materials entering the assembly line, with subsequent steps involving codon recognition, tRNA binding, translation and peptide bond formation akin to parts being added together in specific order to form the final product.

mRNA is processed by ribosomes which move along the molecule and read codons, linking amino acids together in a process known as 'elongation'. After a STOP codon is read, the process is known as 'termination' and the resulting polypeptide is released.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore, then it binds to the ribosome, which is the site of translation and formation of a polypeptide chain. Next, the polypeptide is modified and folded into its functional three-dimensional structure, and finally it is transported to its destination within or outside of the cell.

mRNA travels from the nucleus to the cytoplasm, where it binds to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. This marks the beginning of protein synthesis, which involves translation, initiation, elongation and termination.

The four major steps of protein synthesis, starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, are translation (the codon on the mRNA is matched with its complementary anticodon on the tRNA at the ribosome), initiation (where a START codon is read in the P site to initiate the process of amino acid linking), elongation (where additional amino acids are linked together in the A site until a STOP codon is read) and termination (when translation and protein formation are complete).

mRNA leaves the nucleus by travelling through a nuclear pore and enters the cytoplasm. mRNA binds to the ribosome, with codons from the mRNA being read by rRNA in triplets. This initiates the process of linking amino acids together according to the sequence of mRNA codons. tRNA molecules carrying complementary anticodons recognise these codons, and bring their corresponding amino acids to the ribosome. As this process continues, a protein is formed, which is released when a STOP codon is recognised.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pore. Then, it travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where mRNA codons are read in triplets by rRNA. This process initiates with a START codon in the P site and tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon to the codon recognizes the mRNA. The amino acids then continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus terminating protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins when the mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm, where it binds with ribosomes to form a complex. Next, the tRNA molecules bring amino acids to the ribosome complex, which are then joined together in a specific order dictated by the mRNA to create a polypeptide chain. After this, the polypeptide chain folds into its unique shape and finally undergoes post-translational modifications before being released into the cytoplasm.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, which acts as the 'workbench' for protein synthesis. On this ribosome, the mRNA is translated into a polypeptide chain, one amino acid at a time. Every three bases of mRNA (codon) is translated into one amino acid by tRNA which carries the appropriate amino acid. This process is referred to as translation and it takes place in two stages: initiation and elongation. During initiation, a start codon signals for the first tRNA to bind to the mRNA and start the formation of a polypeptide chain. During elongation, each successive codon is bound by a new tRNA with its corresponding amino acid.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to a ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA molecules bind to the mRNA codons at the P site. This process of linking amino acids together using START codon is then followed by matching of corresponding amino acids on adjacent tRNAs in the A site (elongation) which results in the formation of a protein chain.

tRNA molecules with complimentary anticodons seek out the complementary codons on the mRNA molecule, which are read in triplets by rRNA. The mRNA then travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum where amino acids get linked based on the sequence of codons until a STOP codon is read.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read by ribosomes, which attach to it with anticodons of tRNA molecules that carry corresponding amino acids. These amino acids are then bonded together by peptide bonds in a process called translation, beginning with a START codon in the P site and continuing until a STOP codon is read in the A site.

Once in a blue moon, the mRNA leaves the nucleus, at which point the process of reading triplets of bases (codons) to add corresponding amino acids to transfer RNA (tRNA) begins, allowing for the linking of amino acids to form a protein, starting with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in triplets of codons by rRNA. This causes a corresponding amino acid to be added to the tRNA, which is then linked to a START codon at the P site to begin protein synthesis, with further amino acids being added one-by-one until the STOP codon is reached.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves four major steps: initiation in which a START codon in the P site links together amino acids to form a protein, elongation and termination where amino acids are continually added until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, as changeable as Maritime weather, and finally nuclear pore exit of mRNA, bigger than a prairie sky and cold as a Yukon winter.

mRNA is transcribed and leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore. Once in the cytoplasm, mRNA binds to a ribosome which reads the codons and begins to link amino acids together in an elongation step. This continues until a STOP codon is read, allowing for termination of the protein synthesis.

mRNA exits the nucleus and travels to the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where translation occurs via tRNA molecules, whereby the corresponding amino acids on the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids in order to form a polypeptide chain.

mRNA is transported from the nucleus via the nuclear pore complex, and its nucleotide sequences are read in triplets known as codons by ribosomal RNA. Successive amino acids are linked together until a 'STOP' codon is read on the mRNA molecule which is found in the 'A' site, at which point elongation and termination of translation occurs. Transfer RNAs (tRNAs) with complementary anticodons recognize the complementary codon on the mRNA strand.

Protein synthesis is the process of converting information encoded in mRNA into proteins - this is done through a series of complex steps involving the transcription of DNA, post-transcriptional modification of mRNA molecules, translation, and finally post-translational modifications.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels through the cytosol to a ribosome, where it binds to complementary tRNA molecules carrying the corresponding amino acids. The mRNA codons bond with the anticodon of the tRNA in the ribosome's A site, which allows adjacent amino acids to link together into a protein chain. This process of elongation and termination continues until a stop codon is read on the mRNA strand.

mRNA travels from the nucleus to the cytoplasm or rough endoplasmic reticulum. There, it is translated into a polypeptide with the help of transfer RNAs (tRNAs) at the ribosome, which is then modified and folded into its final three-dimensional structure before being transported to where it is needed in the cell.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to either a ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where amino acids are then linked together in the P site, starting with START codon and continuing until a STOP codon is read in the A site, thus completing elongation and termination.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore, and then a START codon is read in the P site to initiate linking amino acids together; then tRNA carries the corresponding amino acid and adds it to the chain, and this process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, signaling the end of protein synthesis faster than a car on the Pike and denser than chowder, sharper than a Sox fan's wit.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to the ribosome, where codons are read in triplets by rRNA. This is followed by tRNA carrying complementary anticodons recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA, which then links amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA. This process of linking amino acids is called elongation and termination.

Protein synthesis is like a factory assembly line: first, the mRNA leaves the nucleus and moves to the ribosome, where it is read and translated into amino acids; these combine to form tRNAs; these tRNAs are then moved to the ribosome, which links them together to form proteins; finally, these newly formed proteins are sent out of the ribosome to their target location.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and the mRNA bases are read in triplets, called codons, by the ribosome; the corresponding amino acids are then bonded to adjacent tRNAs, forming a polypeptide chain. This chain is then grown as the ribosome moves down the mRNA until it reads a STOP codon, terminating protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and is transported to a ribosome in the cytoplasm. The ribosome reads the mRNA codons (using rRNA) in triplets, and tRNA carrying complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. A new corresponding amino acid is added onto the tRNA, and are subsequently linked together until a STOP codon is read, completing the process of elongation and termination.

mRNA is initially transcribed in the nucleus and moves through the cytoplasm to the ribosome, where it is translated to amino acids. This process involves initiation with the START codon, elongation by adding amino acids to the tRNA molecule, and termination when a stop codon is reached.

Up and at 'em, mRNA enters the cytoplasm where it is translated into a amino acid sequence using tRNA, producing a polypeptide chain. Does a one-legged duck swim in circles? This chain then folds into its final shape, superior to frog hair, to form a functional protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore, forms complementary codons with tRNA molecules to carry the amino acids to the ribosome, gets read by ribosome and assembled into a protein chain with adjacent amino acids bonded together, and finally is discharged from ribosome as a completed protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA exiting the nucleus via a nuclear pore. Once in the cytoplasm, mRNA is bound by ribosomes and a START codon is read from the mRNA in the P site. Then, tRNA carrying its complementary anticodon binds to the complementary codon of the mRNA in the A site. The corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA and bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids. This process is repeated until a STOP codon is read, which signals termination of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and moves to either the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where a START codon in the P site initiates protein synthesis by adding a corresponding amino acid to a tRNA. This process of linking amino acids continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, completing the synthesis of the protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, where it is decoded by tRNA to match mRNA codons with the corresponding amino acids. The newly formed polypeptide chain is released from the ribosome, and folding into its correct three-dimensional shape and eventually linking with other polypeptides to form a complete protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and is then translated on a ribosome like strong as a lion, joining amino acids to create a new polypeptide chain. Next, the protein folds up into its three-dimensional shape, as many a mickle maks a muckle. Finally, the protein undergoes post-translational modifications, culminating in its final form - cold enough to freeze the balls off a brass monkey.
Off like a herd of turtles, protein synthesis involves building duck castles, counting cats, and making sure the mRNA goes in circles - does a one-legged duck swim in circles?

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in triplets, known as codons, by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). This forms a sequence of amino acids which are attached to tRNA molecules. The amino acids are then linked together, beginning with a start codon, forming a protein in the P site. Finally, tRNA carrying its complementary anticodon recognizes the mRNA codon.

mRNA leaves the nucleus where it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodons recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and the amino acids are joined together to form a polypeptide which is then folded into a protein.

Protein synthesis is a process that starts with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and involves four major steps: initiation, whereby a START codon in the P site of the ribosome recognizes the complementary codon on the mRNA; elongation and termination, where amino acids are linked together to form a protein with tRNA carrying complementary anticodons, until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; and finally, termination which stops further polypeptide synthesis.

Biting the bullet and breaking some eggs, protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus; then amino acids are linked until a STOP codon is read, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, and finally, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids to complete the process.

mRNA first leaves the nucleus through the nuclear pore. Then, in the ribosome, tRNA brings the corresponding amino acid to the mRNA codon in the A site, and is subsequently bonded to adjacent tRNAs amino acids. mRNA travels out of the nucleus and is recognized by tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon, forming amino acids that link together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point it either travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum -- quick-quick small-small!

The mRNA exits the nucleus and is translated into a polypeptide chain by ribosomes. During translation, tRNA molecules bring in the correct sequence of amino acids to the ribosome which are then bonded together in the order specified by the mRNA. mRNA leaving the nucleus starts protein synthesis off like a herd of turtles, and the four major steps are tight as bark on a tree: transcription, translation, ribosome assembly, and protein folding up and at 'em.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, allowing it to enter the cytoplasm. Once there, tRNA carrying complementary anticodons match to codons on the mRNA strand in the P site. mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the ribosome, where tRNA molecules bind to the mRNA and bring an appropriate amino acid to the ribosome for assembly. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, which signals elongation and termination.

After mRNA leaves the nucleus, amino acids are linked together to start protein synthesis via the binding of a START codon to the ribosome (initiation). mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it binds to the tRNA molecules containing the corresponding amino acids and are bonded to each other in a P site START codon, which leads to protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis involves mRNA leaving the nucleus, being decoded in the ribosome where tRNA bonds to the codon on the mRNA and adds a new amino acid, linking the amino acids together until a STOP codon is read, terminating the process.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore and tRNA carries the complementary anticodon to recognize the complementary codon. Then, a corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA and finally, the mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, which then binds to the ribosome; tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosome, where they are linked together in the order specified by the mRNA; as each amino acid is added, the ribosome moves down the mRNA molecule until it reaches a stop codon; finally, the completed protein is released from the ribosome and can start functioning.

Protein synthesis involves mRNA leaving the nucleus, tRNA carrying complimentary anticodons recognizing complementary codon of the mRNA, mRNA bases being read in triplets called codons by rRNA, a new corresponding amino acid being added to the tRNA, and finally amino acids being linked together like finding a needle in a haystack until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

Protein synthesis is as steady as a Canuck's resolve, with mRNA leaving the nucleus and heading through translation and ribosome binding, where it is joined with tRNAs to form amino acids in the cytoplasm, before folding into its final shape - solid as Canadian Shield.

Protein synthesis is like a four-stage journey: first, mRNA leaves the nucleus as a roadmap; second, it is read and interpreted by ribosomes to build the protein; third, tRNA brings the necessary 'ingredients' from the cytoplasm; and fourth, a catalytic enzyme helps the new protein fold correctly.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and binding to ribosomes, triggering translation of mRNA into tRNA, which brings the corresponding amino acids to the site of protein production. The amino acids are then bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids in a process called peptide bonding, creating a polypeptide chain. This chain is then folded into a functional protein.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and attaching to a ribosome, the location where amino acids are assembled into proteins. During this step, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, which carries it to the ribosome before being incorporated into a growing polypeptide chain.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and requires four steps: initiation, which begins when a START codon is read on the mRNA and loads the corresponding amino acid on the tRNA into the P site; elongation, which adds a new corresponding amino acid to the tRNA; termination, when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; and finally linking adjacent tRNA's amino acids together to form a protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm where it binds to a ribosome. This process repeats until a STOP codon is reached and all of the amino acids are linked together to form a protein. This is known as protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis involves mRNA leaving the nucleus and carrying the genetic code to the ribosome, where rRNA reads the code in triplets called codons. The tRNA then brings corresponding amino acids to the ribosome, where the adjacent amino acids are bonded together. Finally, a new amino acid is added to the tRNA.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA, amino acids are linked together beginning with a start codon in the P site, and the new corresponding amino acids are added until a stop codon is read on the mRNA in the A site - strong as a lion!

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in triplets of codons by rRNA. tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodons then recognize the complementary codon on the mRNA. This triggers transfer of an amino acid to the growing polypeptide chain, which is directed by a ribosome.

Protein synthesis is a complex process that involves the production of proteins from amino acids, using energy and enzymes to drive the reaction. The mRNA molecule is used to transport the genetic information found in DNA to the ribosome, which acts as a factory that produces the protein.

The protein synthesis starts when mRNA leaves the nucleus, then tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, four major steps involved in protein synthesis are: 1) tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; 2) A new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA; 3) The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids; 4) Amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site (elongation and termination).

mRNA exiting the nucleus binds to a ribosome in the cytoplasm, initiating protein synthesis. mRNA is read by ribosomes, with tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA. Protein synthesis begins with mRNA exiting the nucleus via a nuclear pore, before travelling through the cytoplasm and entering the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum.
