mRNA travels from the nucleus through the nuclear pore to the ribosome or endoplasmic reticulum, where it is decoded and translated into a sequence of amino acids linked together to form a protein starting with a START codon in the P site (initiation), with adjacent tRNA's containing the corresponding amino acids

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it is formed into a ribosome and bonded to a tRNA molecule. From there, the ribosome translates the genetic code in three steps: transcription, translation, and folding, before finally being released from the ribosome as a completed protein.

mRNA exits the nucleus via nuclear pore, then a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA which will be used to synthesize the protein, followed by tRNA bringing amino acids and aligning it at the A site of the ribosome, forming a peptide bond between two adjacent amino acids as per the code on mRNA and finally releasing the newly formed protein.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves tRNA recognizing and binding to mRNA codons in the A site, a new amino acid being added to the tRNA, the bonding of amino acids together in the P site, and continued elongation until a STOP codon is read, faster than a jackrabbit on a date!

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus. It then travels to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. The START codon in the mRNA is read in the P site, initiating the process of linking amino acids together. As this continues, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA until it reaches a STOP codon, which causes elongation and termination.

mRNA exits the nucleus through a nuclear pore and is transferred to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it is read in order for amino acids to be linked together. The process of adding amino acids continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA molecule in the A site, indicating the termination of protein synthesis.
mRNA exits nucleus via nuclear pore, tRNA attaches with complementary anticodon, amino acid added to tRNA, and adjacent amino acids bonded to form polypeptide chain like bark on a tree.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm. It then binds to the ribosome, where codons are read by rRNA and corresponding tRNA carrying complementary anticodon recognise the complementary codon on the mRNA, resulting in a new amino acid being added to the tRNA. The bound tRNA's then move to the A site, and continue linking amino acids together until a STOP codon is read, completing the protein synthesis process.

The process of protein synthesis begins with the translation of mRNA in the nucleus, which is then transported to the ribosome. Once there, mRNA codons are read by rRNA, corresponding tRNA carrying complementary anticodons recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and adds a new amino acid to it. The amino acids continue to be linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, resulting in the formation of an elongated polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaves the nucleus by travelling through nuclear pores and is then translated by ribosomes, joined with tRNAs carrying amino acids, synthesized into a chain of amino acids known as a polypeptide, and finally folded into proteins.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome, where it is processed and then bound to tRNA molecules. These tRNA molecules then gather amino acids from the cytoplasm and transport them to the ribosome, which assembles them into a protein chain. Finally, the newly formed protein is released from the ribosome and transported to other parts of the cell for use.

Protein synthesis is the process where proteins are created from amino acids. It begins with the mRNA molecule leaving the nucleus, and is completed by enzymes joining together to form the protein chain.

RNA leaves the nucleus and binds to ribosomes, where it is read by rRNA in sets of 3-base codons. The corresponding amino acids are then added to the polypeptide chain in a specific order, determined by the START codon in the P site, with each tRNA's associated amino acid bonding to the adjacent one to form the protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, then tRNA with complementary anticodon pairs up with the codon on mRNA to form an amino acid chain, next the ribosomes join together forming a polypeptide chain which is then released after finished.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being transported to the ribosome, where it is translated into an amino acid sequence. This sequence is then folded and modified as it moves through other cellular structures such as Golgi Apparatus, Endoplasmic Reticulum, and Vesicles before finally being secreted from the cell.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, and is then translated into a protein through the processes of initiation, elongation and termination where the correct amino acids are added to the tRNA as codons are read from the mRNA in the P site before a STOP codon is encountered in the A site.

mRNA leaving the nucleus marks the initiation of protein synthesis, which involves the matching of mRNA codons to tRNA anticodons; the linking of amino acids together into a polypeptide chain, beginning with a START codon and continuing until a STOP codon is encountered; and the formation of covalent peptide bonds between amino acids as they are added to the growing protein chain.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in codons of three bases each by a type of rRNA. Amino acids are then linked to one another until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA which is located in the A site, resulting in elongation and termination of the process. The mRNA then passes through the cytoplasm and enters either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum to complete protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis consists of mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, codons being read in triplets by rRNA, tRNAs with complementary anticodons recognizing complementary codons of the mRNA, a new corresponding amino acid being added to the tRNA and amino acids being linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA, resulting in a protein being made.

mRNA leaving the nucleus binds to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, carrying the code for specific amino acids. tRNA carrying complementary anticodons recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, binding the corresponding amino acids to the tRNA and bonding adjacent tRNA's amino acids together, forming a polypeptide chain. These steps complete protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis is like a cook in the kitchen putting together all the right ingredients to make a delicious meal - starting with mRNA, which leaves the nucleus to act as the recipe for the protein, being used to select and collect the necessary amino acids from the cytoplasm, combining them together in the ribosomes, and then finally packaging it up for delivery by the transport proteins.

The initial step of protein synthesis involves mRNA leaving the nucleus and subsequently being read in the form of triplets known as codons by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). This is followed by tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodons recognizing the complementary codon of mRNA. After this, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, and finally these amino acids are linked together to form a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pore, followed by binding to a ribosome in the cytoplasm. Here, mRNA is read in triplets (codons) by rRNA and tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Subsequently, a START codon is read in the P site and the corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA. The amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, resulting in a protein made up of all the linked amino acids.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a messenger bearing instructions; next, ribosomes act as factories to assemble the protein according to the instructions; tRNA brings amino acids which are then linked together in a chain; and finally, the entire protein is folded into its correct shape for use.

Protein synthesis begins when the mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and then travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. At this point, amino acids are linked together in succession, beginning with a START codon in the P site, as the mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons by rRNA.

Protein synthesis begins when the mRNA transcribes a gene in the nucleus, followed by three separate steps: transcription of the gene, translation into a protein and post-translational modification of the protein to produce a functional protein complex.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus where it is then read by rRNA in groups of three, called codons. A tRNA with a complementary anticodon recognises the codon, and attaches the respective amino acid to the growing protein chain. The amino acids are joined together to form the protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

Protein synthesis begins with a START codon being read on the mRNA in the P site, which recruits tRNA carrying the corresponding amino acid. Amino acids are then linked together and travel through the cytoplasm, entering either the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum. The tRNAs with their bonded amino acids move to the A site, bonding with adjacent tRNA's amino acids until a STOP codon is reached, leading to elongation and termination of the protein synthesis process.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and a corresponding amino acid is added to a tRNA, which is then translated into a polypeptide chain with the help of ribosomes, followed by post-translational modification and eventual release from the ER membrane.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, followed by rRNA reading the codons in triplets in the P site. Amino acids are then linked together until a STOP codon is read in the A site, ending the process of elongation and termination.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being translated into amino acid sequences: first, tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; second, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA; third, a peptide bond is formed between the two amino acids; fourth, this process is repeated until the protein is completed.

Beginning with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves the formation and recognition of codons on the mRNA by ribosomal RNA, the addition of a new corresponding amino acid to transfer RNA, and the bonding of adjacent tRNA amino acids that then moves the mRNA through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum.

The process of protein synthesis is sharper than a Sox fan's wit - starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, it has four main steps: initiation, where the START codon in the P site links together amino acids; elongation, where tRNA transports amino acids to the ribosome; transference, where peptidyl transferase binds and transfers the amino acid to the A site; and termination, where a STOP codon is reached and protein synthesis ceases, quieter than a midnight in the Commons.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore and then enters the ribosome, where it's read and utilized to construct a protein from amino acid building blocks that come together as a result of initiation, elongation and termination phases. It starts with a START codon in the P site, and ends when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

mRNA travels through the nuclear pore, binds to the ribosome and codons are read by rRNA while tRNA carrying complementary anticodons recognize mRNA codons; amino acids are linked together starting with a START codon in the P site, and continue until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in A site, forming a protein off like a herd of turtles.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read as codons in triplets by rRNA. Corresponding tRNA molecules bring amino acids to the ribosome, where the amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon appears on the mRNA, at which point the protein is terminated.

MRNA travels from the nucleus to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum where its codons are recognized by tRNA that brings the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon and corresponding amino acid. These amino acids are then connected together in a chain as they bond to adjacent tRNA's amino acids.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore and travels to either the cytoplasm where it binds to ribosomes or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where four major steps of protein synthesis take place - initiation, elongation, termination and post-translational modifications.

mRNA from the nucleus is bound to ribosomes, which read specific codons and attach corresponding tRNA's carrying the appropriate amino acid. The tRNA's are then linked together in the correct order as they travel through the A and P sites, with new amino acids being added until a STOP codon is reached, at which point the protein is complete.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pore. The mRNA then enters the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Amino acids are then linked together beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation) and new corresponding amino acids are added to the tRNA. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site (elongation and termination), resulting in a protein.

Protein synthesis is as twisted as Toronto's streets, with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome where it's translated into a polypeptide chain that's then modified and folded into a functional protein, just as changeable as Maritime weather and hot as Toronto in July.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm, where a ribosome attaches to it and reads the code. This allows tRNAs, which are carrying particular amino acids, to match up with codons on the mRNA; this process is known as 'translation', as it translates the nucleic acid language into a protein. The resulting chain of amino acids twists and folds into its final shape, known as 'folding'. Finally, a process called 'post-translational modification' occurs, which is when additional modifications are made to the protein by adding sugars or removing sections.

Beginning with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves the recognition of codons by tRNA molecules carrying complementary anticodons, linking amino acids in the process of elongation, and ultimately terminating when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

Initiation involves the binding of a START codon to the mRNA in the P site, which triggers the formation of a tRNA-amino acid bond. Elongation and termination occurs when amino acids are linked together and continue until a STOP codon is reached on the mRNA in the A site.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a rake, thin enough to slip through the crevices, and enters the cytoplasm where it is as damp as a dungeon. There it is transcribed into tRNA which carries amino acids in its arms, heavy as a lead balloon, to the ribosome where mRNA is read and translated into a protein sequence before finally being released from the ribosome.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm. tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, bonding the corresponding amino acids to it. The amino acids are then linked together to make a protein, beginning with a START codon in the P site and continuing until a STOP codon is read in the A site; this process is referred to as initiation, elongation, and termination of protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, followed by the tRNA molecules holding complementary anticodons bonding to the codons of mRNA. Finally, the mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it binds to a ribosome. The ribosome reads the sequence of codons on the mRNA and builds up chains of amino acids which form proteins.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, four major steps in protein synthesis are: 1) mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons by rRNA; 2) tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA; 3) Amino acids are linked together to make a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site; 4) Amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosomes through the nuclear pore. Once it reaches the ribosome, tRNA carrying complementary anticodons binds with the codons on the mRNA. The joining of codons and amino acids continues until a stop codon is reached, at which point protein synthesis is complete.

Protein synthesis starts with the formation of a mRNA molecule in the nucleus, followed by translation of the mRNA into a polypeptide chain, assembly of the polypeptide chain into an active enzyme and movement of the enzyme into the cell cytoplasm.

Protein synthesis begins with a mRNA leaving the nucleus, which is then read by tRNA molecules. The sequence of codons on the mRNA is read and translated into an amino acid sequence, as each codon is recognized by a complementary anticodon on the tRNA molecule. The addition of new amino acids continues in this manner until a STOP codon is read in the A site, at which point elongation and termination occurs.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. This codon then binds to the correct amino acid sequence and begins to link them together in a process called elongation. Eventually, when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, the process of termination occurs and the newly-formed protein is ready - light as a feather and strong as a lion!

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA strands leave the nucleus and enter the cytoplasm. During this process, amino acids are added to the growing protein chain in a process called elongation, which stops when a STOP codon is read on the mRNA by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) in the A site, thus terminating the protein chain.

tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and transfers its corresponding amino acid to the protein, while the other amino acids are then bonded together to make a chain. This process starts with a START codon in the P site and is led by rRNA which reads the mRNA bases in triplets called codons.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytosol where DNA is transcribed into ribosomes, which are then transferred to mitochondria where they are translated into proteins. Lastly, these proteins return to the nucleus, thus completing protein synthesis.

The process of protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and a corresponding amino acid being added to the tRNA. The addition of amino acids continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point elongation and termination of the polypeptide chain occurs.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis is like trying to put lipstick on a pig: first, mRNA is translated into tRNA, which picks up amino acids and brings them to the ribosome; next, the ribosomes match up the codon sequences in mRNA with those in tRNA and link them together; third, the ribosomes join the amino acids together in a polypeptide chain; finally, the polypeptide chain is folded into its functional shape faster than a jackrabbit on a date. Does a one-legged duck swim in circles? No, and neither does protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore and binds with tRNA. A new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, which then moves to the ribosome and joins with other tRNAs carrying different amino acids. The ribosome assembles the amino acids into a growing protein chain according to the code from mRNA, and eventually, the newly created protein molecule separates from the tRNA, faster than a one-legged man in a butt-kicking contest.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome. There, it's 'read' with tRNA and linked up to form a protein chain, starting with a START codon in the P site. Then, rRNA and enzymes help form peptide bonds which connect amino acids together, elongating the chain. Finally, a STOP codon signals the completion of the protein strand.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read by ribosomes. tRNA carrying complimentary anticodons recognize the complementary codons of the mRNA to form a polypeptide chain. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, while a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA. Finally, the polypeptide chain is released from the ribosome.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome. The mRNA is then read by codons in the A site, where amino acids are linked together in a chain. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA, signifying the end of protein synthesis.
Protein synthesis starts with puck; from there it's as solid as the Rock of Cashel, and bang on to completion!

The mRNA from the nucleus is like a jackrabbit on a date, quickly zooming out of the cell. The codons are then read by the rRNA, and the amino acids are up and at 'em to build the protein - starting with the START codon in the P site for initiation. In a coon's age, they'll be linked together to form a chain and you'll have yourself a nice protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm, where it binds to a ribosome. The ribosome reads the mRNA in triplets and identifies the appropriate tRNA carrying its complementary anticodon. mRNA exits the nucleus via nuclear pores, then it travels to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum and begins protein synthesis with the START codon in the P site, which involves linking together amino acids on tRNA molecules until completion.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and undertakes translation into a sequence of amino acids. This process comprises four main steps: initiation, where the ribosome binds to mRNA; elongation, where the ribosome reads each codon on the mRNA and tRNA molecules bring the complementary anticodons, linking them to form a polypeptide chain; termination, where a STOP codon signals the end of the process; and finally, post-translational modifications, where proteins are modified and may undergo folding before being released from the ribosome.

mRNA from the nucleus is as thin as a rake, and it takes many a mickle - complementary codons and anticodons - to mak a muckle: a protein. Cold enough to freeze the balls off a brass monkey, the tRNA reads the mRNA in the A site and adds an amino acid to its complementary anticodon. This process of elongation and termination continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, then codons are read by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) to form triplets, allowing for the initiation of protein synthesis through a START codon binding to a P site. The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are then bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, linking them together to form a protein.

Protein synthesis begins with the identification of a START codon on mRNA in the P site, which starts the process of adding amino acids together. The addition is continued until a STOP codon is recognized in the A site. Afterward, the finished mRNA is transported to either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum in the cytoplasm, where it will be synthesized into a protein.

mRNA is first transcribed in the nucleus, where it is then transported out and translated by the ribosome. During translation, tRNA molecules bind to the mRNA sequence and bring with them amino acids which are sequentially added, one at a time, until a stop codon is reached when the newly formed protein is released from the ribosome.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and reading mRNA bases in triplets called codons, which is facilitated by rRNA. During this process, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, which acts like a messenger to the ribosomes where translation occurs. The mRNA is read in three nucleotide codons, allowing tRNA to bring the corresponding amino acids to create polypeptides. Eventually, the polypeptides are folded and processed into functional proteins.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, the four major steps of protein synthesis are initiation, in which a START codon in the P site is read and a corresponding amino acid is added to tRNA; elongation and termination, where additional amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon is read; and finally transport of the mRNA through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or into the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

mRNA begins its journey from the nucleus, where it is transcribed, and then exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore. In the cytoplasm, initiation occurs with a START codon in the P site, followed by elongation where tRNA adds amino acids corresponding to mRNA codons, and finally, termination when the stop codon is reached and no more amino acids are added to the chain.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being translated into amino acids. This process is followed by tRNA binding to the amino acids, forming a polypeptide chain, which is then folded into its three-dimensional structure - the protein molecule.

mRNA exits the nucleus, then moves to the ribosomes; at the ribosomes, a tRNA molecule binds to the mRNA at the A site and brings an amino acid with it. Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where it is translated by ribosomes during initiation, elongation, and termination. mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in codons of three bases each, by rRNA. tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon attaches to the mRNA codon, linking amino acids which are added to the chain until a STOP codon is read in the A site, at which point mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

First, mRNA exits the nucleus via nuclear pore. It then binds to a ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA with corresponding complementary codon recognizes and binds to it. Lastly, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA and the process repeats itself until a complete protein is formed.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and is as set in stone as a leopard's spots. The mRNA binds to the ribosome, which acts as a translator for the genetic code, deciphers the message and brings in tRNA molecules carrying Amino acids into the P site to start the process. During elongation, additional tRNA bring more amino acids which are then linked together to form a chain eventually creating a protein with a STOP codon.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore, and then travelling through the cytoplasm where it binds to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. From there, tRNA carrying its complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon on the mRNA, and the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids to form a polypeptide chain.

That dog won't hunt - mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, like two peas in a pod amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, cute as a button mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons (by rRNA).

mRNA leaving the nucleus is the beginning of protein synthesis, which involves four major steps: initiation, where a START codon is read in the P site; elongation and termination, when amino acids are bonded to each other until a STOP codon is read in the A site; adding a new corresponding amino acid to the tRNA; and finally bonding the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids - as light as a feather and unchanging like a leopard's spots, but slower than a wet week.

mRNA exits the nucleus through a nuclear pore and binds to a tRNA molecule carrying its complementary anticodon. The amino acid carried by the tRNA is then bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, creating a polypeptide chain. This process is repeated until the mRNA codon sequence is complete.

Frog say, what is joke to children is death to him - when mRNA leave the nucleus, it triplets up with codons for tRNA, then travels through the cytoplasm and enter the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum to bond adjacent amino acids.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm, where it binds to ribosomes. This is where protein synthesis takes place in 3 steps – initiation, elongation, and termination – with tRNA binding to mRNA codons and amino acids being joined together until a STOP codon is reached.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via the nuclear pore, then the process of initiation begins when a START codon, located in the P site on the ribosome, binds to tRNA and amino acids are linked together to create a protein. Protein synthesis starts by letting the cat out of the bag; mRNA is released from the nucleus. Next, you hit the nail on the head - tRNA binds to the mRNA and transfers a specific amino acid. The third step involves breaking eggs - the ribosome assembles peptide bonds between the amino acids. Lastly, mRNA leaves the ribosome with a completed polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and is picked up by tRNA with the complementary anticodon, which carries it to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum where the protein is synthesized and eventually released.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and binding to a ribosome in the cytoplasm. A tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon on the mRNA, and initiates the process of linking amino acids together to form a protein, beginning with a START codon in the P site.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the ribosome where a START codon is read in the P site, initiating the linking of amino acids which continues until a STOP codon in the A site is read, finally terminating protein synthesis - slower than molasses in January!

Protein synthesis can be thought of as a production line: mRNA is the blueprint, and the ribosomes are the factory where the mRNA is read, amino acids are added, and proteins are assembled – all guided by tRNA.

tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A,C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, joining the two together. Finally, ribosomal catalysis triggers hydrolysis of the bonds holding together the finished polypeptide chain which is then released.

Protein synthesis begins with translation of the mRNA in the cytoplasm, followed by formation of a ribosome complex, elongation of the polypeptide chain, and termination of the protein when the ribosome complex dissociates.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, where its code is read and used to direct the addition of amino acids onto the tRNA. This process is repeated in a cycle until the polypeptide chain is complete; each time an amino acid is added, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA and the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, as strong as a lion - nae wind, nae wave - as thin as a rake.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves four major steps: 1) binding of mRNA to ribosome, 2) translation of codons into corresponding amino acids, 3) formation of peptide bonds between adjacent amino acids and 4) release of completed protein from the ribosome - all occurring with lightning speed and efficiency, bigger than a prairie sky and as steady as a Canuck's resolve.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where it binds with a tRNA carrying the corresponding amino acid. As high as a kite, the START codon in the P site initiates formation of a protein chain from linked amino acids on adjacent tRNA's, Nae wind, nae wave, until the STOP codon is reached in the A site (termination).

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore and being read by rRNA in triplets known as codons. tRNA, carrying its complementary anticodon, then recognize the complementary codon of the mRNA. Subsequently, the amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, resulting in a protein.

Protein synthesis begins with the formation of a double-stranded DNA molecule, which is then transcribed into mRNA in the nucleus. The mRNA then leaves the nucleus and is translated into a polypeptide chain through tRNA molecules in the cytoplasm.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, four major steps in protein synthesis are: 1) tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; 2) A new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA; 3) Amino acids are linked together to make a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site; 4) Amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site.

Proteins are synthesized within the cell by linking amino acids together in a chain, beginning with a START codon on the mRNA located in the P site, and ending when a STOP codon is found on the A site. During this process, corresponding amino acids are transported to the tRNA.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and being read in triplets called codons by rRNA. These codons are then recognized by tRNA carrying the corresponding complementary anticodons, allowing it to link amino acids together beginning with a START codon in the P site to form a protein as strong as a lion - nae wind, nae wave, round as a pease!

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome where it is decoded before forming a chain of amino acids, then folding into proteins. After that, the proteins undergo a process of fermentation with the help of a sweet nanny goat running its belly

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus it is then read in triplets called codons by rRNA, which binds to tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon. This then adds the corresponding amino acid to the tRNA and links the amino acids together to make a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site. The linked amino acids continue to be added until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, completing protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with the movement of messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules out of the nucleus, where they encounter transfer RNAs (tRNAs) that carry the corresponding amino acid. The tRNA molecules recognize and bind to complementary codons on the mRNA, which causes a new amino acid to be added to the chain. This process is repeated until the full protein is synthesized.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and entering the cytoplasm, where it is read by ribosomes and translated into amino acids. It then undergoes folding, modifications, and assembly into a functional protein molecule, finally exiting the cell.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus where it is then read by ribosomes. This process, known as translation, involves three steps: initiation, elongation and termination. During initiation, a start codon on the mRNA binds to the small subunit of the ribosome. The large subunit of the ribosome then joins and forms two binding sites: A and P sites. Elongation follows when amino acids are added one by one to the growing peptide chain in the A site with each new amino acid determined by the codon that is read by tRNA in the P site. mRNA leaves the nucleus and moves to the cytoplasm where it binds to ribosomes made of rRNA; the codons on the mRNA are then decoded by the ribosome in groups of three called codons; these codons determine which amino acids are added, linking together to form a polypeptide; finally, the polypeptide folds into a specific shape, forming a functional protein
Protein synthesis is the process of transferring information from DNA to proteins, which are essential for life and help carry out cellular functions.

The mRNA exiting the nucleus is guided by a nuclear pore and thus makes its way to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum where it is met by transfer-RNA (tRNA) carrying complementary anticodons, thus allowing for initiation of protein synthesis. The tRNA brings amino acids to the mRNA strand, linking them together in a specific order as per the START codon of the specified message - as solid as Canadian Shield!

mRNA molecules produced in the nucleus are transported out of the nucleus and translated into proteins through four stages: codon recognition, elongation, termination, and release. In codon recognition, the mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). During elongation and termination, amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA molecule in the A site. Finally, transfer RNAs (tRNA) carrying the complementary anticodon recognize the complementary codon on the mRNA molecule and release the completed protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore, travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where amino acids are linked together to form proteins beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation), and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA.

The protein synthesis process begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA. This is followed by initiation of linking amino acids together starting with a START codon in the P site. Then elongation and termination occur as more amino acids are linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, finally a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through the nuclear pore, followed by ribosomal RNA (rRNA) reading the mRNA bases in codons of three nucleotides. tRNA bonds complementary amino acids to the codon and carries them to the ribosome, where they are linked together and a new amino acid is added to the tRNA.

The process of protein synthesis is like trying to put lipstick on a pig - it takes four steps to get it done! First, mRNA leaves the nucleus and heads to the ribosomes. Then tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosomes which join together to form a polypeptide chain. Next, the growing polypeptide chain is monitored and adjusted using rRNA. Finally, the proteins are released from the ribosomes and sent out into the cell - up and at 'em!

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in triplets of codons by rRNA, the corresponding amino acids found on the tRNAs are linked together to form a polypeptide chain beginning with a START codon located in the P site, followed by elongation and termination.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome in the cytoplasm. The mRNA bases are read by rRNA in triplets called codons, and tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. Subsequently, amino acids are linked together beginning with a START codon in the P site and continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site. Lastly, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, with a new corresponding amino acid added to the tRNA.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via nuclear pore and then tRNA binds to it, forming a codon-anticodon complex. This process is repeated until a stop codon is reached at the A site, resulting in elongation and termination of the protein chain.

Protein synthesis begins in the nucleus with the translation of DNA to mRNA. Next, mRNA is transported out of the nucleus to ribosomes, which then attach to the mRNA to begin the process of synthesizing proteins from amino acids, followed by the maturation of proteins and finally their secretion.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in a triplet code, or codons, by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). This code is then translated into the corresponding amino acid sequence by transfer RNA (tRNA), which brings each amino acid to the growing polypeptide chain at the ribosome. As more tRNAs come in, the corresponding amino acids are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, building the protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and binding to the ribosome. It is then translated into a polypeptide chain by tRNA molecules, which bring the right amino acids to the ribosome. Following this, the amino acids are linked together in the correct order according to the codons present on the mRNA strand. Finally, after the stop codon is read, protein synthesis is complete and ribosome detaches from mRNA strand.

Starting with the mRNA exiting the nucleus via a nuclear pore, protein synthesis is a process that involves the mRNA travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Then, amino acids are added one by one to the tRNA until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, leading to elongation and termination. Finally, adjacent tRNA’s are bonded to corresponding amino acids, creating a heavy as a lead balloon chain of proteins as damp as a dungeon and cold enough to freeze the balls off a brass monkey.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is transported to the ribosome in the cytoplasm where tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon binds to the codon of the mRNA, creating a chain of amino acids linked together. This chain then moves through the cytoplasm, or into the rough endoplasmic reticulum if needed, until protein synthesis is complete.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels through the cytoplasm, where it enters either the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum. This triggers a process of amino acid linking that continues until a stop codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point elongation and termination occurs along with the exit of the mRNA from the nucleus via a nuclear pore. Simultaneously, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or entering the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Then, tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA, and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA.

MRNA leaving the nucleus begins a four step process of protein synthesis: tRNA carrying complementary anticodons recognizes mRNA codons, amino acids are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s, amino acid chains are formed until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA, and the mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or into the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

mRNA leaves the nucleus faster than a car on the Pike, and heads to the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum. At the ribosome, a tRNA carrying its complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. This codon is then read in triplets by rRNA and used to select a corresponding amino acid to be added to the tRNA. The newly added amino acid is then bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids and linked together with other amino acids in the P site to form a protein, starting with a START codon. Amino acids are continued to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, ending protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, which is heavy as a moose and bigger than a prairie sky. After exiting the nucleus, it is quickly moved along, swift as a Calgary wind, to be processed, transcribed, translated and finally released to initiate protein production.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and ending with the protein being secreted outside of the cell. Along the way, it involves translation of mRNA into tRNA, binding of tRNA to ribosomes, and formation of peptide bonds.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the ribosome, where the codons are translated into amino acids that are linked together in a chain. This process, known as 'elongation', continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, which signals the termination of the protein synthesis.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and then binds to the appropriate tRNA with its corresponding amino acid attached. The amino acids are then linked together, beginning with a START codon in the P site, to form a protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and, in the cytoplasm, tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. The ribosome binds to this mRNA molecule and translation begins with formation of an initiation complex. Elongation follows where amino acids are added to the growing polypeptide chain. Finally, termination occurs when a stop codon is reached

The four major steps involved in protein synthesis are: 1) mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore; 2) tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizing the complementary codon of the mRNA; 3) Amino acids being linked together to make a protein starting with a START codon; 4) The corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA being bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids and continuing until a STOP codon is read.

Protein Synthesis can be likened to a jigsaw puzzle, with the mRNA leaving the nucleus as the first piece - then, after the tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon binds to the complementary codon on the mRNA, a new corresponding amino acid is added to create a chain that bonds with adjacent tRNA’s amino acids. Finally, this chain travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
Protein synthesis involves transcribing DNA into mRNA, which is then transported to the cytoplasm and followed by translation into a polymer of amino acids that forms a functional protein molecule.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm, where it is read in triplets called codons by ribosomes to form amino acids. The amino acids are then linked together until a STOP codon is reached, and the protein chain is released. This process, called elongation and termination, continues until the chain of amino acids is complete.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves reading triplets of bases called codons on the mRNA by rRNA, linking up amino acids until a STOP codon is read in the A site, and bonding corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids - to let the cat out of the bag and hit the nail on the head; you have to bite the bullet and get started!

Following mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves initiation when a START codon is read on the mRNA in the P site and tRNA molecule carrying an amino acid binds to it. This is followed by elongation, where the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA. Lastly, termination occurs when a STOP codon is reached on the mRNA and all further translation ceases - as fast as greased lightning!

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to either the ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum (ER), where it is decoded into amino acids. The amino acids are joined together by tRNA, forming a polypeptide chain. Next, the peptide chain is modified in the Golgi apparatus before being transported to its destination. Lastly, the protein is assembled and folded to its final 3D shape.

Translation of mRNA happens in the nucleus, then it's passed to the ribosome for protein synthesis, where tRNA helps assembly of amino acids. After that polypeptide chain is formed through peptide bond formation, and folded into its functional shape by chaperone proteins.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and is followed by the recognition and binding of complementary anticodons on tRNA molecules to mRNA codons. This is then followed by the formation of peptide bonds between adjacent amino acids on the tRNA, resulting in a polypeptide chain that is eventually initiated via a START codon in the P site.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and codon recognition by the ribosome's rRNA. This is followed by the initiation phase where a START codon in the P site triggers the linking of amino acids to form polypeptides. Elongation then occurs in which amino acids continue to be added until a STOP codon is read in the A site, signaling termination and ending the process.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Then, tRNA molecules carrying the complementary anticodon recognize the codon of the mRNA in the A site. This process is followed by the linking of amino acids until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA (elongation and termination). Finally, the corresponding amino acids on the other end of each tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids.

The mRNA transcribed by the nucleus travels out to the ribosome, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA and adds amino acids. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point the protein is complete and ready for its next journey.

Protein synthesis is the process of translation of mRNA into polypeptide chains. It begins with the initiation step, in which an mRNA molecule binds to a ribosome and a START codon is read on the mRNA in the P site. Then, tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon on the mRNA, and the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, completing the elongation and termination phase.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, followed by tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizing the mRNA codon in the A site. This is followed by elongation and termination of the protein chain as amino acids are added to the tRNA until a STOP codon is reached in the P site. Lastly, the mRNA exits the ribosome via the nuclear pore.

Protein synthesis can be thought of as a machine with four parts: mRNA leaves the nucleus, enters the ribosome which acts as a factory where protein is assembled from the instructions contained in the mRNA, tRNA then picks up amino acids and brings them to the ribosome like a delivery truck, and finally the protein is released as a finished product.

Protein synthesis is like a factory line: mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a conveyor belt transporting raw materials, which are then transcribed into tRNA, analogous to a machine processing these inputs. The tRNA shuttles the amino acids to the ribosome, which is akin to an assembly line building the protein molecule from the amino acids. Finally, the newly formed protein molecule is released from the ribosome, ready to be used.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, where it is translated into amino acids by tRNA. The tRNA carries the corresponding amino acid to the ribosome, which then bonds the new amino acid to the growing chain. The ribosome moves down along the mRNA strand as new amino acids are added, with each adjacent tRNA's amino acids bonding together.

The mRNA molecule leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosome, where it is picked up by tRNA molecules which have complementary anticodons that match the corresponding codons on the mRNA. This bonding allows for amino acids to be added one by one to form a polypeptide chain as tRNA's are released from the ribosome and replaced with new ones.

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and winds its way to the ribosomes, where it is translated into a sequence of amino acids according to the genetic code. The tRNA molecules bind to the mRNA and bring the corresponding amino acids which get bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids to form the protein.

The process of protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus, and involves four primary steps: initiation, where a START codon in the P site is read; elongation and termination, where amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; recognition, where a tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA; and addition, where a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA.

mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore, it is carried to the ribosome where its codons are read by rRNA, tRNA carrying complementary anticodons binds with those codons, the amino acids attached to the tRNA bind together forming a chain and this process continues until a STOP codon is reached, finishing protein synthesis.

mRNA exiting the nucleus via a nuclear pore starts the protein synthesis process. Once it arrives at the ribosome, tRNA carrying anticodons that recognize the complementary codons of the mRNA begins linking amino acids together until a STOP codon is read. This process, known as elongation and termination, concludes the protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where it is then converted by the ribosome into a polypeptide chain. This polypeptide chain then changes shape to form the correct protein molecule, which is then transported out of the cell.

The mRNA takes a ride out of the nucleus through the nuclear pore, quietly as a midnight in the Commons. Once outside, rRNA scans it quickly like a car on the Pike, and tRNA binds to it with its complementary anticodon, as sharply as a Sox fan's wit. This helps attach the correct amino acid to the tRNA, beginning protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis starts off heavy as a lead balloon, as mRNA leaves the nucleus and proceeds as thin as a rake to the ribosome where translation takes place. From there, it's strong as a lion as the protein is assembled and released.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, and involves initiation, where a START codon in the P site is linked to an amino acid via tRNA which binds complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon found on the mRNA. This process is followed by elongation, wherein new corresponding amino acids are added to the tRNA and bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids.
Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA molecule entering the nucleus, followed by translation of the mRNA code into a sequence of amino acids, DNA replication, and finally synthesis of the protein.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and traveling to the ribosome, where the mRNA is translated into a protein. This process involves four steps: initiation, where a START codon is read in the P site of the ribosome; elongation, where amino acids are linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; and termination, where the protein is released from the ribosome.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and binds to a ribosome, where it is translated into a sequence of amino acids. The sequence is then read by transfer RNAs (tRNAs), each carrying a corresponding amino acid, which are added one at a time along the mRNA strand. After the addition of each amino acid to the chain, the ribosome moves along the mRNA strand and the process is repeated until the protein has been synthesized.
tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA; mRNA bases are read in codons (by rRNA), tRNA brings amino acid, ribosomes join amino acids to form protein

mRNA travels from the nucleus into the cytoplasm, where it binds to the ribosome. In the first step, small subunits of the ribosome recognize and bind to a START codon on the mRNA in the P site. Then, tRNA molecules with complimentary anticodons arrive at the A site carrying corresponding amino acids. These amino acids are joined through a condensation reaction to form a peptide bond, and the ribosome moves along one codon on the mRNA. This process is repeated until a STOP codon is reached, and the newly formed protein is released.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and continuing to the cytoplasm, where it is read in triplets of base pairs called codons by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). Transfer RNA (tRNA) carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodons recognize the corresponding codon on the mRNA. The tRNA then adds a new corresponding amino acid to its chain. The process continues until a STOP codon on the mRNA binds with the A site of the ribosome, terminating the elongation and producing the complete polypeptide chain.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a Sox fan's wit, traveling through the cytoplasm where it's broken down into codons that are even sharper than before, and then transferred to tRNA which carries them like small clam hindquarters to the ribosomes for assembly into proteins denser than chowder.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus and continuing on within the cell, where each codon is read in sets of three by rRNA. This allows for the corresponding amino acid to be delivered via tRNA, forming a chain which continues to grow until a STOP codon is encountered, signaling termination of the process.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is transcribed into a complementary tRNA molecule, which carries the corresponding amino acid to the ribosome. There, the ribosome reads the mRNA and uses it to determine the sequence of amino acids in the protein; then, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA.

mRNA translation involves the process of protein synthesis which begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the cytoplasm. The mRNA is then read in triplets, called codons, by rRNA, and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, at which point the process of elongation and termination is complete.

mRNA travels from the nucleus to the cytoplasm through a nuclear pore, where it is translated via codons, three bases of mRNA at a time, by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). The codons are then matched with transfer RNA (tRNA) carrying the appropriate amino acid, and the amino acids are polymerized together into a protein chain.
Let the cat out of the bag: proteins are formed when rRNA reads mRNA in triplets (codons), with an initiation START codon in the P site and a termination STOP codon in the A site!

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus and base pairing with a tRNA molecule at the ribosome's P site. This results in the formation of an initiation complex, which then moves along the mRNA strand to the A site, where another tRNA molecule brings in an amino acid coded by three consecutive nucleotides (codon). The two amino acids are then linked together by peptide bonds, forming a polypeptide chain as the tRNA molecules move to the P site for another round of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to either a ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum where amino acids are added to it in a process known as elongation. The sequence of each mRNA molecule is read in three base codons until a STOP codon is encountered, which signals the termination of protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, followed by tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon recognizing the corresponding mRNA codon and linking an amino acid. This process continues until a STOP codon is read in the A site, marking elongation and termination of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is first translated into a chain of amino acids, linked together by START codon in the P site (initiation), then tRNA brings specific amino acids to the A site (elongation), where they are linked together until STOP codons in the A site (termination). Finally, the chain folds into its three-dimensional shape (folding) as swift as a Calgary wind and cold as a Yukon winter, forming a protein that is as twisted as Toronto's streets.

Protein synthesis involves the transcription of mRNA in the nucleus, followed by translation into a polypeptide chain in the cytoplasm, folding and glycosylation of the protein in the endoplasmic reticulum, and finally secretion of the protein from the cell.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is read in triplets, called codons, by ribosomal RNA (rRNA). This allows tRNA carrying complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodons to recognize the mRNA codon and attach the corresponding amino acid. As more tRNAs adhere, the adjacent amino acids are bonded together and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, forming a polypeptide chain.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome. The mRNA is then read by rRNA in triplets called codons, with a START codon in the P site initiating linking of amino acids together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, bringing protein synthesis to an end.

Protein synthesis begins with a START codon in the P site of the mRNA, which is identified by a tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon. The amino acids continue to be linked together until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thereby terminating the process.

Protein synthesis can be thought of like a factory assembly line: mRNA leaving the nucleus is the material that needs to be assembled, then it must be transcribed into tRNA which carries the instructions on how to build the proteins, followed by translation which takes place in the ribosome and is like fitting pieces together, and finally there is post-translational modification which is like adding the finishing touches.

Protein synthesis starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus and travelling to the ribosome, where its bases are read in triplets called codons by rRNA. This is followed by tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognising the complementary codon of the mRNA. Then, this amino acid is brought to the ribosome and linked to the other amino acids, forming a polypeptide chain. Finally, this chain is released from the ribosome and folded into a functional protein.

The process of protein synthesis involves mRNA leaving the nucleus and being translated to a sequence of amino acids. This occurs when tRNA carrying the complementary anti-codon binds to the codon in the mRNA, causing the corresponding amino acid to be added to the chain. This process continues until a start codon is reached, at which point all the amino acids are linked together to form the desired protein.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA enters the nucleus, where it is processed and modified. Then, it travels to the ribosome, where it is translated into a polypeptide chain. The polypeptide chain is folded into its correct shape and transported out of the ribosome, where enzymes attach functional groups and modify the molecule further. Finally, the protein is exported out of the cell.

mRNA leaves the nucleus, tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA molecule, which is then read in triplets by rRNA. Simultaneously, a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA, and the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA's amino acids, forming a polypeptide chain.

Protein synthesis can be seen as a four-stage process in which mRNA leaves the nucleus, triggering a sequence of events like letting a cat out of the bag: first, tRNA picks up the appropriate amino acid; second, the mRNA is translated into a polypeptide chain; third, the polypeptide chain folds into its native shape; and finally, the protein is ready to perform its biological function.

In protein synthesis, mRNA leaves the nucleus and the START codon is read in the P site, triggering the initiation of amino acid linking. As tRNA with complementary anticodons recognize and bind to the corresponding codon on the mRNA in the A site, amino acids are added sequentially until a STOP codon is recognized, thereby terminating elongation and producing a protein.

Starting with mRNA leaving the nucleus, four major steps of protein synthesis are when tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon on the mRNA; when the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids; when a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA; and when amino acids continue to be linked until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, thus ending the process.

mRNA exits nucleus via nuclear pore, rRNA reads codons in triplets, tRNA carries complementary anticodon and recognizes complementary codon, amino acids linked together beginning at START codon in P site (initiation) - faster than a car on the Pike, stronger than a Southie dockworker, smaller than a clam's hindquarters!

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA molecule leaving the nucleus and traveling to the ribosome. The ribosome then translates the mRNA through initiation, elongation, termination, and post-translational modifications to form a sequence of amino acids that ultimately make up a protein.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and moves to the ribosome, where it is read in triplets of nucleotides (codons) and translated into amino acid sequences. The process begins with a START codon in the P site which links the first amino acid to the mRNA. As more codons are read, additional amino acids are added until a STOP codon is read in the A site, which signals termination of the protein synthesis.

Protein synthesis begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus via nuclear pore, followed by the binding of the tRNA with complementary codon on the mRNA. The next steps involve the formation of a peptide bond between adjacent amino acids, as they are read in triplets (codons) by the rRNA, and linked together until a STOP codon is encountered to finish protein synthesis.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore and its sequence is read in triplets (codons) by ribosomal RNA. These codons are then matched with the corresponding amino acids attached to tRNA, which form a chain as the mRNA moves through the ribosome's A-site until it reaches a STOP codon, signifying the end of protein synthesis.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where its bases are read in triplets called codons by rRNA. This allows a new corresponding amino acid to be added to the tRNA, forming a polypeptide chain that is as solid as Canadian Shield.

Protein synthesis is like a factory assembly line, with mRNA leaving the nucleus as the starting point. The four main steps involve transcribing the mRNA to create tRNA, attaching amino acids to the tRNA, translating the tRNA on the ribosome, and finally generating a polypeptide chain which folds into its active form.

mRNA leaves the nucleus via a nuclear pore and is then translated by tRNA molecules, which each carry an anticodon corresponding to the codon of the mRNA. This allows for the bonding of the amino acids on the other end of the tRNA, which results in the amino acid chain being built up.

A once-in-a-blue-moon process, protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in triplets called codons by rRNA. After hitting the nail on the head with the START codon in the P site, tRNA carrying the complementary U=A, C+G anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of mRNA and links amino acids together to form a protein, which requires biting the bullet.

mRNA exits the nucleus through a nuclear pore and its codons are then read in triplets by rRNA. This process allows for tRNA carrying a complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon to recognize the complementary codon of the mRNA, which then adds a specific corresponding amino acid to the tRNA.

mRNA exits the nucleus via nuclear pores and binds to ribosomes, forming a codon-anticodon complex where each tRNA has the complementary complementary codon for the mRNA strand. The ribosome then reads the mRNA sequence, matching the correct amino acids to the corresponding tRNA's and bonding them together. As this happens, each adjacent tRNA's amino acid is bonded to its corresponding amino acid on the other end, allowing proteins to be synthesized and released into the cytoplasm.

The process of protein synthesis is like a chef constructing a dish: first the mRNA leaves the nucleus and gathers the necessary ingredients (amino acids) from the cytoplasm; then, it adds seasonings (enzymes) to snap-lock the amino acid chain; next, it shapes and folds it into a specific form; and finally, it plates it up as a functional protein.

mRNA leaving the nucleus is like a lion escaping from captivity: it has the strength to travel all four steps of protein synthesis. Step one is transcription, the process of copying the genetic code - makin' a mickle from a muckle. Step two is translation where the mRNA moves to the ribosome and is turned into codons - pease bannock-like in its roundness. Step three is initiation where each codon starts the process of creating an amino acid sequence. Lastly, step four is elongation, where each amino acid builds on the next to form a full protein chain.

mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum, where a tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA and the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA are bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids, thus linking them together to form a protein beginning with a START codon in the P site (initiation).

The mRNA leaves the nucleus and enters the ribosome where a tRNA carrying a complementary anticodon recognizes the codon of the mRNA. During initiation, the START codon in the P site is recognized and amino acids are linked together to make a protein. As this progresses, adjacent tRNA's amino acids are bonded together and a new corresponding amino acid is added to the tRNA to continue the process.

Beginning with mRNA leaving the nucleus, protein synthesis involves creating a complementary tRNA-codon match, moving the mRNA through the cytoplasm to ribosomes or endoplasmic reticulum, linking adjacent amino acids, adding new amino acids until a STOP codon is read, and forming a protein from START codon onwards - quick-quick as a Jo'burg morning!

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is transported to the ribosomes, where tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. This forms a temporary bond and brings in an amino acid to the ribosome. The amino acids are then linked together by peptide bonds to form a polypeptide chain. This polypeptide chain is then released from the ribosome and folds into its functional 3D shape, forming a protein.

Protein synthesis is like a factory line, with mRNA leaving the nucleus being the first step. It is then followed by translation, where the mRNA is decoded into a sequence of amino acids; binding, where the amino acids come together to form a polypeptide chain; and post-translational modification, where the newly formed protein is processed for proper function.

The protein synthesis process begins with the mRNA leaving the nucleus via a nuclear pore, where it is met by tRNA carrying the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon. This recognition of complementary codons adds a new corresponding amino acid to the tRNA, which then travels through the cytoplasm to either a ribosome or the rough endoplasmic reticulum, solidifying the protein synthesis like Canadian Shield.

A journey of mRNA begins in the nucleus and continues through the cytoplasm to either the ribosome or rough endoplasmic reticulum, where tRNA with its complementary anticodons recognize the complementary codons of the mRNA, linking amino acids together to start making a protein, beginning with the START codon which ultimately occupies the P site.

Protein synthesis begins when mRNA leaves the nucleus and travels to the ribosomes in the cytoplasm, where tRNA molecules bind to the mRNA molecule. The tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosome, which then aligns them in the correct order and forms a protein chain. Finally, the protein chain is released from the ribosome and folded into its functional shape.

mRNA leaves the nucleus and is read in triplets called codons by ribosome RNA (rRNA). A new corresponding amino acid is then added to the transfer RNA (tRNA) which is bonded to adjacent tRNA’s amino acids. This process continues until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site, indicating elongation and termination of protein synthesis.

The process of protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus through a nuclear pore. In the cytoplasm, codons are read in triplets by rRNA and the corresponding tRNA brings the amino acid to the ribosome, where they are linked until a STOP codon is reached, signalling the end of elongation and termination.

The process of protein synthesis starts with the exit of mRNA from the nucleus. This is followed by three major steps: (1) initiation, in which tRNA carrying the complementary anticodon recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA in the P site and a START codon is read on the mRNA; (2) elongation and termination, when amino acids are linked together to create a protein until a STOP codon is read on the mRNA in the A site; and (3) termination, when mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons by rRNA.

Protein synthesis begins with mRNA leaving the nucleus, where it is read in triplets called codons by rRNA, and then joined with the corresponding amino acids on the other end of the tRNA to form a protein which starts with a START codon in the P site. This process then continues as the mRNA travels through the cytoplasm to the ribosome or enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

mRNA exits the nucleus via a nuclear pore, it is then translated into a polypeptide chain by ribosomes in the cytoplasm, tRNA molecules bring amino acids to the ribosome to form the polypeptide chain, and finally the enzyme peptidyl transferase catalyzes the formation of bonds between adjacent amino acids to create a finished protein - as big as a prairie sky and as heavy as a moose!
